# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cricket
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The 100-ball game has two teams each having a single innings, which is restricted to a maximum of 100 balls, and the match lasts approximately two and a half hours, shorter than the Twenty20 format.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Before the launch of the professional The Hundred competition in July 2021, the 100-ball format was trialled in several amateur local leagues across England.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The new 100-ball format was born out of a proposal by the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) in 2016 to launch a new franchise cricket competition, similar to the Indian Premier League.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] At first it was expected that the competition would use the existing Twenty20 format.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Following discussions involving the ECB's marketing team, clubs were instead told in April 2018 that the competition would use an entirely new form of cricket designed to be simpler to follow and shorter to fit television schedules.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The more detailed proposal was presented by the ECB to the chair and chief executives of the first-class counties and the MCC on 19 April 2018, and was unanimously supported by the board of the new competition.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] At first it was proposed that each innings would involve 15 six-ball overs and a final 10-ball over.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] In February 2019, the ECB announced tweaks to the proposed rules of 100-ball cricket.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The competition will instead contain 10 ten-ball overs, i.e. a change of ends after ten balls.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] A bowler will be delivering five or 10 consecutive balls.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] A bowler would deliver a maximum of 20 balls per innings.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Power-play conditions were also announced.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Trial events using the format took place at The Purchasers annual cricket festival at Belmont House in Kent, and club level in England.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] In November 2018, the Warwickshire Cricket Board and Warwickshire County Cricket Club launched the 100-ball format club level tournament, which is designed to revitalise Sunday cricket at clubs across the Midlands.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Called the Warwickshire Sunday Smash, the 16 team tournament is split into three divisions, with each side playing each team both home and away, throughout June and July.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The teams include Solihull Blossomfield Cricket Club, Knowle & Dorridge, Sutton Coldfield, Bedworth, Alcester & Ragley, Stratford upon Avon, Water Orton, Four Oaks Saints, Moseley Ashfield and Aston Manor, who are all members of the Midlands Club Cricket Conference.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The winners of each league and the best second place progressing to the Semi-Finals Day.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The Finals Day took place on 1 September 2019 at Edgbaston.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Stratford Upon Avon beat Knowle & Dorridge to win the first 100-ball competition in the UK.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Shropshire County Cricket Club introduced the Swancote Energy Smash, which began in June 2019.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] It is a six-team tournament that has been divided into two groups, with games being played every Thursday night.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The winners of each group is due to play in the inaugural final in early September 2019.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The six teams are Shifnal, Claverley, Worfield, Bridgnorth, Chelmarsh and Wombourne.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] In May 2021 Shropshire Cricket league launched two 100-ball knock out competitions, known as the Aaron's 100 and Aaron's Premier 100, involving 53 teams from across Shropshire and mid-Wales.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Cricket Wales launched the Cricket Wales U19’s 100 Ball Cup for under 19 year olds.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] It started on 25 June 2021 and is due to end with the final on 13 August 2021 at Ynystawe Cricket Club.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The Cricket Paper National Girls U18 100 Ball Cup was established by Shrewsbury School.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Originally known as the Shrewsbury School Girls U18 T20 in 2019, it is now a 100-ball cricket competition.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The first professional competition using the 100-ball format was The Hundred in July 2021.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The Hundred involves eight men's and women's teams across England and Wales.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The first professional match using the new format involved the women's teams of the Oval Invincibles and Manchester Originals who played each other at The Oval in London on 21 July 2021.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The Africa Cricket Association plans to hold an annual 100-ball competition to further boost the game within the continent.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] 100-ball cricket is a form of limited overs cricket, played by two teams each playing a single innings made up of 100 balls.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] English journalist George Dobell wrote in 2018 that proposals for the new format outlined by the ECB were nothing more than a further step towards "fast-food cricket", whereas others support the proposals.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] England's then Test captain, Joe Root, welcomed the ECB's plans for its new-team format in 2020.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] According to Root, it will attract a completely new audience.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] ODI and T20 captain, Eoin Morgan, had a similar opinion about this format.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Former T20 captain Stuart Broad said he was hugely optimistic about the new format.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Michael Vaughan also echoed Broad and stated that it will be a more appealing concept to broadcasters.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Michael Atherton shared that a T20 match was originally to be completed in a 3-hour window and this can be achieved with the proposed format.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] New Zealand all-rounder Jimmy Neesham was bemused on this move, asking why the England and Wales Cricket Board is trying something different when the current format is already so successful.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Current limited overs specialists Dawid Malan and Mark Wood shared that in spite of the new format, T20s will still remain as the preference.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Former MCC chief Keith Bradshaw called the 100-ball tournament an innovation for innovation's sake, reasoning that the main reason behind this thought process is that the ECB could not exploit the T20 boom.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] The England and Wales Professional Cricketers' Association shared that, overall, players were open to this new idea.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] Meanwhile, Cricket Australia has no plans to tinker with its existing Big Bash League.
[src:cricket/100-ball-cricket] It also shared a concern that the introduction of shorter formats is further ignoring Test cricket.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:cricket/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The **1748 English cricket season** was the zenith of single wicket, never so popular before or since.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] A total of 18 significant single wicket matches are in the records, compared with a mere handful of eleven-a-side games.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] 1748 was the zenith of single wicket, and numerous matches were organised from June to September.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] On an unknown date early in the month, Tom Faulkner defeated Robert Colchin by one wicket.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Colchin scored 40 and 5; Faulkner scored 45 and 1*.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] A "fives" game on Monday, 5 June took place on the Artillery Ground between Addington and The Rest, excluding Kent.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Addington's players were Tom Faulkner, Joe Harris, John Harris, George Jackson, and William Durling (described as "the shoemaker that lately came out of Kent").
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Their opponents were Stephen Dingate, Little Bennett, Maynard, Collins, and Thomas Waymark.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] This appears to be the first time that a team specifically called "The Rest" was ever assembled.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Three "servants of the Duke of Richmond" played Three of London at the Artillery Ground on Friday, 24 June.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The result is unknown but the match started quite late at four o'clock.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Richmond's team was Stephen Dingate, Joseph Rudd, and Pye; London's three were Little and Tall Bennett, and William Anderson.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The match was reported in the *London Evening Post* on Saturday, 25 June.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] On Saturday, 25 June a return match between Colchin and Faulkner took place on Addington Hill.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] He made 7 and 12; Faulkner replied with 11 and 6.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] A third game between Colchin and Faulkner, "each having previously won one", was held on the Artillery Ground, Monday 4 July.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Unfortunately, there are no match details this time.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] On the same day, also on the Artillery Ground, Thomas Waymark and Darville played as Two of Berkshire against Little Bennett and George Smith of London.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Smith was allowed an unnamed substitute in the field.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Darville was the owner of Bray Mills, where Waymark worked at this time.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Smith, apparently having resolved his financial problems, was still the landlord of the famous *Py'd Horse* and keeper of the Artillery Ground.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] A "fives" match was played Wednesday, 6 July on the Artillery Ground.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Tom Faulkner's Side beat Stephen Dingate's Side by one wicket.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Two runs were required when the last man went in.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The teams were: Tom Faulkner, Joe Harris, William Anderson, and Little and Tall Bennett versus Stephen Dingate, Joseph Rudd, Pye, James Bryant, and John Bryant.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The same two teams of "fives" met again from Wednesday, 13 to Friday, 15 July.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] This match was also on the Artillery Ground.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Play was interrupted by rain on the Wednesday after one team had completed its first innings, scoring 13.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] No further details are known but, as an apparent "decider" was played on Wednesday, 27 July, perhaps Dingate's team won this one.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] On Wednesday, 27 July, there was another "fives" game between the Faulkner and Dingate teams on the Artillery Ground.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] This match may have been a decider; in which case Dingate's team must have won the second match on Friday, 15 July.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The teams were not the same as before: Dingate, Richard Newland, Joseph Rudd, Maynard (of Surrey), and Little Bennett played against Faulkner, Joe Harris, William Durling (of Addington), James and John Bryant.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The Artillery Ground staged two matches on Monday, 8 August.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] First, Tom Faulkner and Joe Harris played Robert Colchin and Val Romney at "twos" for twenty guineas a side.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Immediately afterwards, there was the return of the Waymark/Darville versus Bennett/Smith game, with Smith again allowed a substitute fielder.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] A "fives" game was played Saturday, 20 August on the Artillery Ground.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The teams were: Robert Colchin, John Colchin, James Bryant, John Bryant, and Robert Lascoe against Joe Harris, Maynard, John Capon, William Anderson, and Walker.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] This is the only known mention of the player called Walker.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] On Monday, 22 August, a "fives" game was played on the Artillery Ground for 20 guineas a side between Five of Berkshire and Five of London.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Berkshire's team was Thomas Waymark, Darville, and three others.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The London players were William Anderson, Little and Tall Bennett, John Capon, and George Carter.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Tom Faulkner's Five defeated Long Robin's Five on Monday, 29 August, by four runs.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The match was played at the Artillery Ground for a prize of £200.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Val Romney was badly injured and could not run but, the rules being *play or pay*, he was obliged to play as well as he could.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The teams were Faulkner, Joe Harris, James Bryant, John Bryant, and William Durling against Colchin, Romney, Maynard, John Larkin, and Jones.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] There were four known matches this month, all of them played on the Artillery Ground.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] On Monday, 5 September, there was an odds match between Three of England and Five of Berkshire for 20 guineas.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The teams were Robert Colchin, Tom Faulkner, and George Smith against Thomas Waymark and four others of Berkshire.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] George Smith was not allowed a substitute (termed a "Seeker-out" in the primary source) as in previous games, and had to do his share of the fielding.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] On Friday, 16 September, Colchin and Waymark teamed up to defeat Faulkner and Joe Harris.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] It was announced beforehand that "in case of rain, there is good shelter for the spectators".
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Apparently, the match gave such great satisfaction that an immediate return was arranged.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Colchin & Waymark scored 10 and 17, against 0 and 15.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] In their first innings, Faulkner and Harris were both bowled second ball.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Details were reported in the *London Evening Post* on Saturday, 17 September.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The return was played next day for fifty guineas.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Colchin and Waymark again defeated Faulkner and Joe Harris.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Finally, a "threes" game was played Friday, 23 September "for a considerable sum".
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Colchin, Waymark, and Maynard met Faulkner, Joe Harris, and John Bryant.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Two Kent v England matches were played 10 and 13 June on Dartford Brent and the Artillery Ground respectively.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Kent won the first by 11 runs, and the second by an unknown margin.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] London defeated Lambeth 14 June on Peckham Rye Common, as reported by the *Whitehall Evening Post* on Thursday, 16 June.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] London also played against Croydon on 18 July, and Deptford & Greenwich on 15 August.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Both matches were on the Artillery Ground, but the results are unknown.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] On 23 August, Deptford & Greenwich hosted London on "Mr Siddle's new cricket-ground at Deptford".
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] George Smith, keeper of the Artillery Ground and landlord of the adjoining *Pyed Horse* in Chiswell Street, declared bankruptcy.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] Evidently his pricing problems of recent years did have some basis in needing to balance the books after all.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] A number of notices appeared in the press during the first six months of 1748 but Smith eventually resolved his problems, perhaps through the sale of other property, and was able to retain control of the Artillery Ground until 1752.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] There was a game played 4 August on Coxheath Common between teams representing "the Hill" and "the Valley".
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] This sounds like a similar idea to the early match at Chevening in the year 1610; and may have been commemorative.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] In 1748, an action of Jeffreys v Parsons was heard before the King's Bench.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The case concerned wagers that were almost certainly made on the above two Kent v England games, with Jeffreys claiming 25 guineas won from Parsons on each game.
[src:cricket/1748-english-cricket-season] The parties came to an out of court agreement after the case was held over.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] This article describes the history of Australian cricket from the 1876–77 season until 1890.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] An England cricket team toured Australia and New Zealand in the winter of 1876–77 and, in March 1877, took part with Australia in the first two matches to be designated as Tests.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] The 1876–77 Australian cricket season focused on the touring England team and featured no first-class matches between the colonies.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] New South Wales, Victoria and Tasmania were unable to arrange fixtures as in previous seasons.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] Club cricket matches were played in most of the colonies.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] In 1877–78, South Australia in its inaugural first-class match defeated Tasmania by an innings and 13 runs at the Adelaide Oval, this being the initial first-class match at that famous venue.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] New South Wales defeated Victoria twice.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] At the Melbourne Cricket Ground, NSW won by an innings and 6 runs.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] Then, in the initial first-class match at the Sydney Cricket Ground, NSW won by 1 wicket.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] The colonies continued to arrange matches against each other on an *ad hoc* basis through the 1880s.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] For details of the matches, see: Intercolonial cricket in Australia and List of Australian intercolonial cricket matches.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] The lists below give the leading first-class runscorers and wicket-takers in each domestic season.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] In addition, England played a first-class match against New South Wales at the Albert Cricket Ground in Sydney.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] All the other games played, mostly against odds, were not first-class.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] This included the New Zealand leg of the tour.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] England played 23 matches in total of which they won 11, lost 4 and drew 8.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] For further details of this and the next three tours by England, see History of Test cricket from 1877 to 1883.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] James Lillywhite of Sussex was both the tour organiser and England team captain.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] His party included five Yorkshire players: Tom Emmett, George Ulyett, Tom Armitage, Allen Hill and Andrew Greenwood.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] The other players were Harry Jupp, James Southerton, Ted Pooley (all of Surrey); Henry Charlwood (Sussex); John Selby and Alfred Shaw (both of Nottinghamshire).
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] The England team was otherwise known as Lord Harris' XI, after its captain, the tour having been organised by the Melbourne Cricket Club.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] In all matches, the team played 15, won 6, drew 6 and lost 3.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] In five first-class matches including the Test match, the tourists won 2 and lost 3.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] No first-class matches were played in New Zealand but four first-class matches in addition to the Test match were played in Australia.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] These were versus New South Wales (twice) and Victoria (twice).
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] A riot occurred when the tourists played New South Wales, which is more fully described in the article on the Sydney Riot of 1879.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] The England team, captained by Ivo Bligh, was on its famous quest "to recover those Ashes", a reference to the famous RIP notice that was published in the aftermath of England's defeat by Australia at The Oval during the previous English season.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] Originally, three Tests were arranged and England won two of these after losing the first.
[src:cricket/1876-77-australian-cricket-season] Further details of this and the next two tours can be found in the article History of Test cricket from 1884 to 1889.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The **1975 Cricket World Cup** (officially called the **Prudential Cup '75**) was the inaugural men's Cricket World Cup, and the first major tournament in the history of One Day International (ODI) cricket.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Organised by the International Cricket Conference (ICC), it took place in England, between 7 June and 21 June 1975.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was sponsored by Prudential Assurance Company and had eight participating countries: the six Test-playing teams of the time – Australia, England, India, New Zealand, Pakistan, the West Indies – and the two leading Associate nations at the time – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The teams were divided into two groups of four, with each team playing each other in their group once; the top two from each group qualified for the semi-finals, with the winners of these matches meeting in the final.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match consisted of 60 overs per side and was played in traditional white clothing and with red balls; all were played and ended in daylight.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] England and New Zealand finished as the top two teams in Group A, while the West Indies finished top of the Group B table ahead of Australia as the four teams qualified through to the semi-finals.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia defeated England and the West Indies defeated New Zealand in the semi-finals, the West Indies which came into the tournament as favourites, defeated Australia in the final at Lord's by 17 runs to become the first World Cup winners.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] New Zealand batsman, Glenn Turner was the top run-scorer for the tournament with 333 runs, whilst Australian bowler Gary Gilmour was the top wicket-taker with 11 wickets despite only playing in the final two matches.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first multilateral cricket competition at international level was the 1912 Triangular Tournament in England.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was played between the three test nations at the time – England, Australia and South Africa.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The concept was later dropped because of inclement weather and a lack of public interest.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first one-day match to occur was in 1962 when four English county cricket teams filled in a gap to play in a limited overs knockout competition.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was won by Northamptonshire who defeated Leicestershire by five wickets.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The limited-over format had been used in what sponsors marketed as a 'World Cricket Cup' in England in 1966 and 1967, contested between England, a Rest of the World XI, and a touring team (the West Indies in 1966 and Pakistan in 1967).
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The marketing of the event was clearly influenced by the hosting of the 1966 FIFA World Cup in the same country.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The 1966 'World Cricket Cup' was won by England, that in 1967 by the Rest of the World.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] A report in the *Cricketer* implied that the last such match in this "Triangular Tournament", between Pakistan and the Rest of the World was neither well-attended nor taken entirely seriously: "It was a pity that a larger crowd was not present ...
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Sobers took the Cup and the World Xl took the gold medals.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was not until 1971 that the first official One Day International (ODI) took place at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG) as a replacement for the third test of the 1970–71 Ashes series between Australia and England.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to a deluge of rain that had affected the match for the first three days of the test.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match was a forty over match with each over being eight deliveries.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] After England made 190 from 39.4 overs, Australia chased the target at a steady rate to secure the match with 42 balls remaining.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Two years later at Lord's during the 1973 Women's Cricket World Cup, plans were made for a men's tournament to take place in 1975.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was planned to involve all the Test nations at the time in two group stages with the top two in each group qualifying for the knockout stage with the final at Lord's.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The format of the 1975 Cricket World Cup had the eight teams split into two groups of four, with each team playing the others in their group once.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played over 60 overs per side with group stage matches scheduled to take place between 7 and 14 June.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played entirely during day, with a cut off time of 7.30 pm.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Three days were allocated to each match with each able to be continued if they were halted for rain or bad light.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group advanced to the semi-finals on 18 June, with the winners qualifying for the final at Lord's on 21 June.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight teams were invited to compete at the World Cup: the six full members of the International Cricket Conference (ICC), and two other teams – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] South Africa was not allowed to complete due to the sporting boycott of the country which took place during apartheid era, the ICC having placed a moratorium on tours of the country in 1970.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began the teams were split into two groups.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The ICC made the decision to place the two teams which were not Test playing countries in separate groups.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] They also decided to place England and Australia in separate groups and to do the same with India and Pakistan.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Six grounds were used to host matches during the tournament.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The announcement of venues began on 26 July 1973 when the ICC announced that the tournament would be played, with Lord's as the venue for the final.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The remaining venues were announced on 5 November 1974, with the scheduling for the tournament announced alongside that for the five county cricket tournaments that would take place during the 1975 season.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Other than Lord's, which hosted only one group stage match, and The Oval which hosted three, each of the grounds was used for two matches during the group stage.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Headingley and The Oval were the grounds chosen for the two semi-finals.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began each team named a squad of 14 players.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Heading into the first Cricket World Cup, the Ladbrokes betting agency had the West Indies as the favourites at 9–4.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was followed by England at 11–4 with Pakistan and Australia in third and fourth respectively.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] East Africa was last in the betting odds at 1500–1.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the tournament, most of the teams played in warm-up matches against English county teams to get used to the English conditions with most of the national teams getting wins.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only East Africa, Sri Lanka and India lost at least one warm-up match before the tournament.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia played in Canada, losing to Eastern Canada and drawing with Toronto, before heading to England.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight days before the World Cup, the ICC declared in a unanimous decision that any of the balls that went over a batsman's head would be called wide due to the fast short-pitched bowling.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The opening round of matches took place on 7 June with four matches being played.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match at Lord's saw England deliver the highest score by a team in the 60 over match with 334 runs being scored.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Dennis Amiss top scored for the English with 137 from 147 balls helped by Keith Fletcher and Chris Old who each recorded a half-century.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Sunil Gavaskar batted through the entire innings for only 36 runs off 174 balls, prompting Gulabrai Ramchand to speculate that he was treating the match as batting practice.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia opened their campaign with a win against Pakistan at Headingley with a 73-run victory.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to Dennis Lillee's five-wicket haul which brought Pakistan's hope of a win crashing down as they collapsed from 181 for four to be all out for 205.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Earlier, Ross Edwards top scored for Australia with 80 as he aided the Australians in getting 94 runs from the last 13 overs to bring Australia to 278 for seven from their 60 overs.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other two matches saw easy wins for the West Indies and New Zealand.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Glenn Turner, he occupied the crease during the whole New Zealand innings as he top scored with 171 as New Zealand won by 181 runs over East Africa.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies took a nine-wicket victory over Sri Lanka who became the first team to score under 100 runs in a One Day International.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Despite missing two players due to operation – Asif Iqbal – and examinations – Imran Khan – Pakistan was not fazed by the missing players in the second round of games with the team scoring 266 for seven from their 60 overs with standing captain Majid Khan top scoring for Pakistan with 60.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies fell to 166 for eight which included a period of three wickets for only 10 runs as Bernard Julien, Clive Lloyd and Keith Boyce all losing their wickets.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] But the last wicket pair of Deryck Murray and Andy Roberts stole the match away as the West Indies won by a wicket off the final over.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] On the field, Alan Turner scored a century as Australia ended with 328 with Sri Lanka falling 52 runs short as John Mason from *The Daily Telegraph* stated that they might not have many new admirers with their short ball stuff sending two Sri Lankan batsman to hospital.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Group A saw two convincing wins to England and India.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] At Trent Bridge, Keith Fletcher top scored for England with 131 as he guided the English to their second victory and going to the lead of the group table with an 80-run win over New Zealand.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other match in Group A saw 720 spectators observe India record a 10-wicket victory with Madan Lal taking three wickets for India, after East Africa were all-out for only 120.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the match sold out four days in advance, the West Indies took on Australia to see who would finish top of Group B.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the ball swinging in the air, the pair of Rod Marsh and Ross Edwards guided Australia to 192 with a 99-run partnership for the sixth wicket after Australia fell to 61/5.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies went on to take a seven-wicket victory with Alvin Kallicharran top scoring with 78, which included a period of 31 runs of nine Dennis Lillee deliveries as the West Indies finished top of Group B.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan ended their tournament with a 192-run victory over Sri Lanka at Trent Bridge with half centuries to Zaheer Abbas, Majid Khan and Sadiq Mohammad.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] In Group A, New Zealand sealed their spot in the semi-finals with a four-wicket victory over India off the back of a century from Glenn Turner as he hit twelve fours on his way to an unbeaten innings of 114.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only Ramesh Sethi offered much resistance, lasting for 32 overs to score 30.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The knockout stage of the Cricket World Cup consisted of two single-elimination rounds leading to a final.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] If the match was delayed due to rain there were two reserve days to play out the match.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first semi-final was between England and Australia at Headingley.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Australia, their one change in bringing in Gary Gilmour for Ashley Mallett proved critical in booking Australia's spot into the final.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to the grassy pitch that both captains would criticise after the match.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia elected to field first, Gilmour took six wickets for 14 runs as he had England at 37 for seven after he bowled his 12 overs.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Mike Denness attempted to bring England back but would lose his wicket as England fell for 93.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] In the run-chase, Australia collapsed to 39 for six before Gilmour partnered with Doug Walters as they chased the remaining runs to earn Australia a berth in the final.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The second semi-final was between the West Indies and New Zealand at The Oval.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Batting first, New Zealand reached 92 for only one loss at the lunch break.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] After lunch though, they collapsed to 158 with Geoff Howarth top scoring for New Zealand with 51, while Bernard Julien was the top wicket taker with four wickets.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] The final match on 21 June was sold out three days beforehand.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the West Indies being favourites for the match, they were asked by Ian Chappell to bat first and would go on to score 291 for eight wickets from 60 overs.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] After being given a second chance from a Ross Edwards dropped chance at mid-wicket, Clive Lloyd went on to top score for the West Indies with 102.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Gary Gilmour was the best of the Australian bowlers with five wickets for 48 runs.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Ian Chappell scored a half-century to set up the foundation for Australia before three run-outs from the hands of Viv Richards put the pressure on Australia as they collapsed to 233 for nine.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] A final-wicket partnership of 41 from Dennis Lillee and Jeff Thomson brought Australia within 18 runs of victory.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] But a fifth run-out of the innings saw Australia bowled out for 274 and would see the West Indies win by 17 runs, claiming the first men's World Cup.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Glenn Turner of New Zealand ended the tournament as the leading run scorer for the 1975 edition with his 333 runs coming in four games which included an unbeaten 171 against East Africa, which was also the highest score of the tournament.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] In second place was English player Dennis Amiss with Pakistan's Majid Khan rounding out the top three.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australian player Gary Gilmour was the tournament's leading wicket taker with 11 wickets from his two games, which included the best tournament figures in the semi-finals when he took six wickets for 14 against England.
[src:cricket/1975-cricket-world-cup] Bernard Julien and Keith Boyce (both from the West Indies) finished in second place, both getting 10 wickets for the tournament.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The **2008 Mumbai attacks**, colloquially known as **26/11**, were a coordinated series of twelve Islamic terrorist attacks carried out in Mumbai, Maharashtra, India, from 26 to 29 November 2008, by ten members of the Lashkar-e-Taiba.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A total of 175 people died, including nine of the attackers, and more than 300 were injured.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers arrived in Mumbai via the Arabian Sea.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They departed from Karachi on a Pakistani cargo vessel, hijacked an Indian fishing trawler on the way, and ended their journey to South Mumbai's coastline on inflatable boats.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Eight of the attacks were mass shootings in South Mumbai at Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus, Trident Hotel, Taj Mahal Palace Hotel, Leopold Cafe, Cama Hospital, Nariman House, Metro Big Cinemas, and in a lane behind St.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Xavier's College and the headquarters of *The Times of India*.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In addition to the mass shootings, an explosion occurred at Mazagaon, in Mumbai's port area, and in a taxi at Vile Parle.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] By the early morning of 28 November, all sites except for the Taj Hotel had been secured by the Mumbai Police and security forces.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 29 November, India's National Security Guards conducted Operation Black Tornado to flush out the remaining terrorists; it culminated in the death of the last remaining terrorists at the Taj Hotel and ended the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Before his execution in 2012, Ajmal Kasab, the sole surviving attacker captured by the Mumbai Police, stated and confessed that the terrorists were members of the Lashkar-e-Taiba and were controlled from Pakistan, corroborating initial claims from the Indian government.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Although initially denying the claims, Pakistan later confirmed that the sole surviving perpetrator of the attacks was a Pakistani citizen.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The capture of Zabiuddin Ansari aka Abu Hamza in July 2012, an Indian national radicalised by Lashkar-e-Taiba, provided further clarity to the plot.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 9 April 2015, the foremost suspected ringleader of the attacks, Zakiur Rehman Lakhvi, was released on bail in Pakistan and disappeared.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] He evaded capture for years, until being arrested again in Lahore on 2 January 2021.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In 2018, former Pakistani prime minister Nawaz Sharif questioned the Pakistani government's allowing men who had committed the attacks to cross into India.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In 2022, one of the masterminds of the attack, Sajid Mir —who the Pakistani government had earlier said was dead — was convicted for funding terrorist activities by an anti-terrorism court in Pakistan and sentenced to 15 years in prison.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attacks strained diplomatic relations between India and Pakistan, and made a huge impact on law enforcement and security officials to deal with such scenarios in the future.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attacks also caused a major political impact on the then ruling government led by the United Progressive Alliance, as the same year, several other cities suffered from Islamic terrorism, which were also perpetrated by Pakistani terror groups.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Many terrorist attacks had occurred in Mumbai since the 13 coordinated bomb explosions that killed 257 people on 12 March 1993.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The 1993 attacks were carried out as revenge for the earlier Bombay riots, in which many Muslims were killed.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Between March 1993 and July 2006 Mumbai city saw 12 notable incidents of bomb attacks resulting in the death of 516 people and injuries to 1952.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Whereas all of these were bomb attacks, the November 2008 Mumbai attacks were *fidayeen* or suicide attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 6 December 2002, a blast in a BEST bus near Ghatkopar station killed two people and injured 28.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The bombing occurred on the 10th anniversary of the demolition of the Babri Mosque in Ayodhya.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A bicycle bomb exploded near the Vile Parle station in Mumbai, killing one person and injuring 25 on 27 January 2003, a day before the visit of the Prime Minister of India Atal Bihari Vajpayee to the city.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 13 March 2003, a day after the 10th anniversary of the 1993 Bombay bombings, a bomb exploded in a train compartment near the Mulund station, killing 10 people and injuring 70.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 28 July 2003, a blast in a BEST bus in Ghatkopar killed 4 people and injured 32.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 25 August 2003, two bombs exploded in South Mumbai, one near the Gateway of India and the other at Zaveri Bazaar in Kalbadevi.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At least 44 people were killed and 150 injured.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 11 July 2006, seven bombs exploded within 11 minutes on the Suburban Railway in Mumbai, killing 209 people, including 22 foreigners and more than 700 injured.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] According to the Mumbai Police, the bombings were carried out by Lashkar-e-Taiba (LeT) and Students Islamic Movement of India (SIMI).
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A group of men said to number between 24 and 26 received training in marine warfare at a remote camp in mountainous Muzaffarabad in Pakistan.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Part of the training was said to have taken place on the Mangla Dam reservoir in Pakistan.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] From the recruits, 10 were handpicked for the Mumbai mission.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They also received training in swimming and sailing, besides the use of high-end weapons and explosives under the supervision of LeT commanders.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] According to a media report citing an unnamed former Department of Defense official of the US, the intelligence agencies of the US had determined that former officers from Pakistan's Army and Inter-Services Intelligence agency assisted actively and continuously in training.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They were given blueprints of all the four targets – The Taj Mahal Palace Hotel, Oberoi Trident, Nariman House, and Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] After setting sail from Karachi, the terrorists hijacked an Indian fishing boat and killed four people on board.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The boat's captain was kept alive for navigation; he was later killed.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The first events ashore were detailed around 20:30 Indian Standard Time (IST) on 26 November, when 10 men in inflatable speedboats (counts vary) landed at two locations in Colaba.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They reportedly told locals and fishermen (counts vary) who asked them who they were that they were students and to "mind their own business".
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The terrorists further split up into groups of two with each going their separate way either on foot or via taxi.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus (CSMT) was attacked by two gunmen including Ajmal Kasab.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attack began around 21:30, when the two enter the passenger hall and open fire with AK-47 assault rifles and grenades.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Onsite security personnel are heavily outgunned.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Three are killed confronting the terrorists.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Announcements by a railway announcer, Vishnu Dattaram Zende, alerts passengers to leave the station, which saves many lives.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers kill 58 people and injure 104 others, their assault ending at about 22:45.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] While moving away from the railway station, the attackers pass a police station.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Knowing that they are outgunned against the heavily armed terrorists, the police officers at the station, instead of confronting the terrorists, decide to switch off the lights and secure the gates.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers then head in the direction of Cama Hospital.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Sounds of gunfire alert the hospital staff and they take precautionary measures.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] This includes locking the patient wards, switching off the lights and silencing mobile phones.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The terrorists move through the hospital for around 50 minutes.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A police team reaches the hospital and a shootout takes place on the sixth floor.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Two police officers are killed and five are injured including Sadanand Date after which the terrorists leave the hospital complex.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A team of the Mumbai Anti-Terrorist Squad, led by Police Chief Hemant Karkare, search the Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus and then leave in pursuit of the two terrorists after receiving a wireless message that Sadanand and his team have been injured in a firefight.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The terrorists open fire on the police vehicle in a lane next to the hospital and receive return fire in response.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Karkare, Vijay Salaskar, Ashok Kamte, and three of their constables are killed.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The only survivor, Constable Arun Jadhav, is severely wounded however he pretends to be dead.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The terrorists seize the police vehicle but later abandon it and seize a passenger car instead.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They then run into a police roadblock, which had been set up after Jadhav radioed for help.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A gun battle then ensues in which Kasab is wounded and the other terrorist is killed.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A police officer, Tukaram Omble, is killed when he tries to disarm Kasab by wrestling his weapon away from him.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] After a physical struggle with other police personnel, Kasab is arrested.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Kasab was immediately taken to a government hospital where he was also interrogated.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At around 05:30 he was brought to Rakesh Maria at the police control room for further questioning.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Among other things, Kasab stated that there were just ten of them, and that they were suppose to die fighting.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] During this time, attacks were going on at other locations including the two five star hotels, Taj and Oberoi Trident.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The Leopold Cafe, a popular restaurant and bar on Colaba Causeway in South Mumbai, was one of the first sites to be attacked on 26 November.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Accounts vary with regard to when exactly the attack on Leopold Cafe took place and its duration.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They place the start of the attack between 21:15 and 21:40, while the duration of the attack varies between just over two minutes and 45 minutes.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The two attackers kill 10 people, including some international visitors, and injure many more.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers then head for Taj Mahal Palace Hotel a short distance away.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The nearest police station was 200 meters away.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Sounds from the attack on the cafe reached the police station.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Screaming pedestrians ran past the station.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The duty inspector logged the time of the incident as 21:45.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers had moved on by the time police arrive at the cafe.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Sounds of gunfire could still be heard, now some distance away.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Within minutes there are around two dozen police personnel at the cafe.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Following messages on the walkie-talkie police personnel head in the direction of the gunshots and Taj Hotel.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Two pairs of terrorists hailed taxis to go to their target.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] During these journeys they left time bombs in the vehicles.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The first explosion took place at Wadi Bunder between 22:20 and 22:25.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Three people, including the driver of the taxi, were killed, and about 15 others were injured.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The second one occurred at 22:40 at Vile Parle, killing the driver and a passenger.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A total of 10 bombs were planted during the entire course of events.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In addition, police seized a boat filled with arms and explosives anchored at Mazgaon dock off Mumbai Harbour.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The terror attack on the 565 room five star Taj Hotel lasted for 59 hours.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] It began when two terrorists enter the hotel from the front entrance on 26 November at around 21:25 and 22:30.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Before entering the hotel they place an IED at the entrance.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The two terrorists who had attacked Leopold Cafe had by this time had also entered the hotel.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The four terrorists then move through the hotel causing more casualties.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Multiple explosions are reported from the hotel.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In one instance the terrorists plant a bomb on the fifth floor below the central dome.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Its explosion causes structural damages.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They also start a fire on the sixth floor causing huge plumes of smoke.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Mumbai Police are the first responders, they are soon assisted by the army and navy commandos.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Firefighters rescue 200 hostages from windows using ladders during the first night.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They also incorrectly believed that the Taj Palace and Towers had been cleared of attackers, and soldiers were leading hostages and holed-up guests to safety, and removing bodies of those killed in the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] However, later news reports indicated that two or three attackers were still in the Taj, with explosions heard and gunfire exchanged.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Fires were also reported at the ground floor of the Taj, with plumes of smoke arising from the first floor.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The final operation at the Taj Palace hotel was completed by the NSG commandos at 08:00 on 29 November, killing three attackers and resulting in the conclusion of the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Several members of the European Parliament Committee on International Trade were staying at the Taj Hotel when it was attacked, but none were harmed.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] British Conservative Member of the European Parliament (MEP) Sajjad Karim (who was in the lobby when attackers initially opened fire there) and German Social Democrat MEP Erika Mann were hiding in different parts of the building.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Also reported present was Spanish MEP Ignasi Guardans, who was barricaded in a hotel room.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Another British Conservative MEP, Syed Kamall, reported that he along with several other MEPs left the hotel and went to a nearby restaurant shortly before the attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Kamall also reported that Polish MEP Jan Masiel was thought to have been sleeping in his hotel room when the attacks started, but eventually left the hotel safely.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Kamall and Guardans reported that a Hungarian MEP's assistant was shot.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Also caught up in the shooting were Indian MP N.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Krishnadas of Kerala and Gulam Noon while having dinner at a restaurant in the Taj Hotel.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Gautam Adani, a billionaire business tycoon of India, was having dinner in the Taj on November 26; he hid in the hotel kitchen and later in the toilet, and came out safely the next morning.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A total of 36 civilians were killed inside Taj Hotel.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Major Sandeep Unnikrishnan of the NSG was fatally shot during the rescue of Commando Sunil Yadav, who was hit in the leg by a bullet during the rescue operations at Taj.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The Oberoi and Trident hotels are a luxury hotel complex having over 800 rooms.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attack started on 26 November between 21:35 and 22:20.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Before entering the hotel, a pair of terrorists placed an IED at the entrance of the hotel.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] After firing at guests in the lobby and in one of the restaurants they placed another IED there as well.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers then moved upwards through the 33 floor Trident Hotel taking hostages as they progressed.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The modus operandi followed was similar to the attack taking place at the Taj.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The first call to the police was at 21:51.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Within minutes police personnel reached the hotel.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] An outer cordon was established and some civilians were rescued.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] While at this stage there was a confrontation between the terrorists and the police, the outgunned police backed away.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Eight marine commandos arrived at around 02:00 on the 27th and engaged the terrorists however heavy gunfire and grenades limited their progress.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] NSG commandos reached the hotel at 07:00 on the 27th.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Rooms were entered using a master key and searched one by one.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They came across the attackers on reaching the 18th floor of the hotel at 17:30.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Operations continued into the 28th when the attackers were killed at around 15:00.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] During the attack one of the terrorists called up an Indian news channel and the subsequent conversation was aired nationally.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] When reports emerged that attackers were receiving television broadcasts, feeds to the hotels were blocked.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] President of Madrid, Esperanza Aguirre and her accompanying trade delegation were in the hotel premises during the attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] 32 hostages were killed at the Oberoi Trident.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Nariman House, a Chabad Lubavitch Jewish centre in Colaba known as the Mumbai Chabad House, run by Gavriel Holtzberg and his wife, was taken over by two attackers on the 26th at around 21:20, and several visiting residents were held hostage.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Police were notified of gunfire in the area around one hour later.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At least 300 locals from adjacent buildings were evacuated and gunfire was exchanged with the attackers.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At around midnight on the 27th, 9 hostages were rescued from the first floor.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] NSG officers did a recce at 15:00 on the 27th.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Attempts are made to ascertain the layout of the interiors of Nariman House.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On the 27th in the morning the Holtzbergs' two year old son had managed to escape with his caregiver.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The three had been taken to a nearby police station.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] By 18:00 NSG had set up an inner cordon and placed its snipers.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] It was getting dark and the NSG had no night vision equipment.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] However at 21:30 electricity to the building was cut and a probe team attempted entry.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A grenade was thrown from inside causing the NSG probe team to withdraw.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At around 22:00 Indian intelligence intercepted a call between the terrorists at Nariman and their handlers regarding killing the hostages.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] NSG was informed about the death of the hostages only after a delay.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The mission had now changed from hostage rescue to seek and destroy.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] During this time more than 60 civilians were shifted from surrounding buildings.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] It was now 01:00 on the 28th when the civilian evacuation was considered complete.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The NSG realised that the police may have initially made an overestimate with regard to the number of terrorists.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The terrorists continued firing single shots throughout the night, changing positions as they did so.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] It was decided to enter the building at dawn from the roof.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Commandos were positioned on an adjacent building with a commanding view of the drop off point.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] There were two 84mm Carl Gustav rocket launchers incase the terrorists attacked the helicopter.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Three AK47s were borrowed from Mumbai Police for these commandos.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The gloves for fast-roping could not be found so makeshift gloves had to be made.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At 07:05 the helicopter arrived with 20 commandos with MP5s.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Hundreds of locals and television crews crowded to view the spectacle.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Live telecast of the helicopter and the commandos helped the handlers provide information to the terrorists.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The terrorists prepared themselves on the fourth floor of the five story building by shifting around objects to make makeshift pillbox shaped structures.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The commandos clear the fifth floor, still making sure there were no civilians.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The door to the fourth floor was closed which was breached using an explosive charge.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The first commando to enter, Gajender Singh Bisht, was shot by a terrorist, and brief gunfire is exchanged.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A grenade thrown by the terrorists injures two commandos.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Retrieving the body of Bisht becomes a priority.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] To this end the officer incharge ordered all surrounding units to fire and tear gas canisters are also thrown in.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] During this firing one of the terrorists was injured.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Intercepted communication between the terrorist and his handler also conveys the same.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A new entry to the fourth floor was needed.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At 17:00 on the 28th the explosive creates a hole in a wall, stunning the terrorists.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Commandos enter the room and after a momentary gunfight the two terrorists were killed with no more loss of life to the NSG.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On the second floor more hostages were found dead.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] David Kilcullen writes that the Holtzbergs' had been "horrifically tortured".
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The search regarding the identity of the terrorists started during the first attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] During the searches, an unknown group calling itself the Mujahideen Hyderabad Deccan claimed responsibility for attacks in an email, which was later traced to Pakistan and was regarded as hoax.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The Mumbai attacks were planned and directed by Lashkar-e-Taiba militants inside Pakistan and carried out by 10 young armed men trained and sent to Mumbai and directed from inside Pakistan by mobile phones and VoIP.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In July 2009, Pakistani authorities confirmed that LeT plotted and financed the attacks from LeT camps in Karachi and Thatta.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In November 2009, Pakistani authorities charged seven men they had arrested earlier, of planning and executing the assault.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Mumbai police department originally identified 37 suspects—including two Pakistan Army officers—for their alleged involvement in the plot.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] All but two of the suspects, many of whom are identified only through aliases, are Pakistani.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] David Coleman Headley and Tahawwur Hussain Rana, arrested in the United States in October 2009 for other attacks, were also found to have been involved in planning the Mumbai attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] One of these men, Pakistani American David Headley (born Daood Sayed Gilani), was found to have made several trips to India before the attacks, and gathered video and GPS information on behalf of the plotters.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In April 2011, the United States issued arrest warrants for four Pakistani men as suspects in the attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Three men, Sajid Mir, Abu Qahafa, and Mazhar Iqbal, alias "Major Iqbal", were believed to be members of Lashkar-e-Taiba, and helped plan and train the attackers.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Pakistani Prime Minister Yousaf Raza Gillani and President Asif Ali Zardari condemned the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Pakistan promised to assist in the investigation, and President Zardari vowed "strong action against any Pakistani elements found involved in the attack".
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Pakistan initially denied that Pakistanis were responsible for the attacks, blaming plotters in Bangladesh and Indian criminals, a claim refuted by India, and saying they needed information from India on other bombings first.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Pakistani authorities finally agreed that Ajmal Kasab was a Pakistani on 7 January 2009, and registered a case against three other Pakistani nationals.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The Indian government supplied evidence to Pakistan and other governments, in the form of interrogations, weapons, and call records of conversations during the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In addition, Indian government officials said that the attacks were so sophisticated that they must have had official backing from Pakistani "agencies", an accusation denied by Pakistan.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Pakistan arrested a few members of Jamaat ud-Dawa and briefly put its founder under house arrest, but he was found to be free a few days later.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A year after the attacks, Mumbai police continued to complain that Pakistani authorities were not co-operating by providing information for their investigation.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Meanwhile, journalists in Pakistan said security agencies were preventing them from interviewing people from Kasab's village.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Chidambaram said the Pakistani authorities had not shared any information about American suspects David Headley and Tahawwur Hussain Rana, but that the FBI had been more forthcoming.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] An Indian report, summarising intelligence gained from India's interrogation of David Headley, was released in October 2010.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] It alleged that Pakistan's intelligence agency (ISI) had provided support for the attacks by providing funding for reconnaissance missions in Mumbai.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The report included Headley's claim that Lashkar-e-Taiba's chief military commander, Zaki-ur-Rahman Lakhvi, had close ties to the ISI.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In 2018, during an interview with newspaper *Dawn*, Pakistan's former Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif questioned Pakistan's inaction in preventing the Mumbai attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] According to investigations, the attackers travelled by sea from Karachi, Pakistan, across the Arabian Sea, hijacked the Indian fishing trawler *Kuber*, killed the crew of four, then forced the captain to sail to Mumbai.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] After murdering the captain, the attackers entered Mumbai on a rubber dinghy.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The captain of *Kuber*, Amar Singh Solanki, had earlier been imprisoned for six months in a Pakistani jail for illegally fishing in Pakistani waters.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers stayed and were trained by the Lashkar-e-Taiba in a safehouse at Azizabad in Karachi before boarding a small boat for Mumbai.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] David Headley was a member of Lashkar-e-Taiba, and between 2002 and 2009, Headley travelled extensively as part of his work for LeT.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Headley received training in small arms and countersurveillance from LeT, built a network of connections for the group, and lead in scoping out targets for Mumbai attack having allegedly been given $25,000 in cash in 2006 by an ISI officer known as Major Iqbal.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The officer also helped him arrange a communications system for the attack and oversaw a model of the Taj Hotel, so that gunmen could know their way inside the target, according to Headley's testimony to Indian authorities.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Headley also helped ISI recruit Indian agents to monitor Indian troop levels and movements, according to a US official.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At the same time, Headley was also an informant for the US Drug Enforcement Administration, and Headley's wives warned American officials of Headley's involvement with LeT and his plotting attacks, warning specifically that the Taj Hotel may be their target.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] US officials believed that the ISI officers provided support to LeT militants who carried out the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In the hours after the attack, the New York City Police Department sent Brandon del Pozo, an official from their intelligence division, to investigate the incident to understand what vulnerabilities its methods posed for New York City.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The arrest of Zabiuddin Ansari, alias Abu Hamza, in June 2012 provided further clarity on how the plot was hatched.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] According to Abu Hamza, the attacks were previously scheduled for 2006, using Indian youth for the job.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] However, a huge cache of AK-47s and RDX, which were to be used for the attacks, was recovered from Aurangabad in 2006, thus leading to the dismantling of the original plot.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Subsequently, Abu Hamza fled to Pakistan and along with Lashkar commanders, scouted for Pakistani youth to be used for the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In September 2007, 10 people were selected for the mission.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In September 2008, these people tried sailing to Mumbai from Karachi, but could not complete their mission due to choppy waters.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] These men made a second attempt in November 2008, and successfully managed to execute the final attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] David Headley's disclosures that three Pakistani army officers were associated with the planning and execution of the attack were substantiated by Ansari's revelations during his interrogation.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] After Ansari's arrest, Pakistan's Foreign Office claimed they had received information that up to 40 Indian nationals were involved in the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 7 May 2025, the Muridke camp was destroyed in a missile strike by the Indian Armed Forces in retaliation for the Pahalgam terrorist attack, which was also perpetrated by the Lashkar-e-Taiba.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The strikes reportedly killed Lashkar's HQ chief Mudassar aka Abu Jundal (not to be confused with 26/11 co-conspirator Zabiuddin Ansari who used the alias Abu Jundal) among several other terrorists.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers had planned the attack several months ahead of time, and knew some areas well enough to vanish and reappear after security forces had left.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Several sources have quoted Kasab telling the police that the group received help from Mumbai residents.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers used at least three SIM cards purchased on the Indian side of the border with Bangladesh.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] There were also reports of a SIM card purchased in the US state of New Jersey.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Police had also mentioned that Faheem Ansari, an Indian Lashkar operative who had been arrested in February 2008, had scouted the Mumbai targets for the November attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Later, the police arrested two Indian suspects, Mikhtar Ahmad, who is from Srinagar in Kashmir, and Tausif Rehman, a resident of Kolkata.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They supplied the SIM cards, one in Calcutta, and the other in New Delhi.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers used a satellite phone and cell phones to talk to each other, as well as their handlers who were based in Pakistan.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In transcripts intercepted by Indian authorities between the attackers and their handlers, the handlers provided the attackers with encouragement, tactical advice, and information gained from media coverage.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers used both personal cell phones and those obtained from their victims to communicate with each other and the news media.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Although the attackers were encouraged to murder hostages, the attackers were in communication with the news media via cell phones to make demands in return for the release of hostages.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] This was believed to be done to further confuse Indian authorities that they were dealing with primarily a hostage situation.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Type 86 grenades made by China's state-owned Norinco were used in the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Also, indications arose that the attackers had been taking cocaine.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The gunman who survived said that the attackers had used Google Earth to familiarise themselves with the locations of buildings used in the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Of the 10 gunmen, nine were subsequently shot dead and one was captured by security forces.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Witnesses reported that they seemed to be in their early 20s, wore black T-shirts and jeans, and smiled and looked happy as they shot their victims.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Initially, some of the attackers reported to be British citizens, but the Indian government later stated that there was no evidence to confirm this.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Similarly, early reports of 12 gunmen were also later shown to be incorrect.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Dera Ismail Khan is in the North-West Frontier Province; the rest of the towns are in Pakistani Punjab.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 6 April 2010, the Home Minister of Maharashtra, informed the assembly that the bodies of the nine killed Pakistani gunmen from the 2008 attack on Mumbai were buried in a secret location in January 2010, although several organizations advocated for a sea burial.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The bodies had been in the mortuary of a Mumbai hospital after Muslim clerics in the city refused to let them be buried on their grounds.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Only one of the attackers, Ajmal Kasab, survived the attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] He was hanged in Yerwada Central Jail in 2012.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Ajmal Kasab was the only attacker arrested by police.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At first, he deposed to police inspector Ramesh Mahale that he had come to India "to see Amitabh Bachchan's bungalow", and that he was apprehended by the Mumbai Police outside the bungalow.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Much of the information about the attackers' preparation, travel, and movements comes from his subsequent confessions to the Mumbai police.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 12 February 2009, Pakistani Interior Minister Rehman Malik said that Pakistani national Javed Iqbal, who acquired VoIP phones in Spain for the Mumbai attackers, and Hamad Ameen Sadiq, who had facilitated money transfer for the attack, had been arrested.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Two other men known as Khan and Riaz, but whose full names were not given, were also arrested.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Two Pakistanis were arrested in Brescia, Italy (east of Milan), on 21 November 2009, after being accused of providing logistical support to the attacks and transferring more than US$200 to Internet accounts using a false ID.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They had Red Corner Notices issued against them by Interpol for their suspected involvement and it was issued after the last year's strikes.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In October 2009, two Chicago men were arrested and charged by the FBI for involvement in "terrorism" abroad, David Coleman Headley and Tahawwur Hussain Rana.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Headley, a Pakistani American, was charged in November 2009 with scouting locations for the 2008 Mumbai attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Headley is reported to have posed as an American Jew and is believed to have links with militant Islamist groups based in Bangladesh.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 18 March 2010, Headley pleaded guilty to a dozen charges against him thereby avoiding going to trial.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In December 2009, the FBI charged Abdur Rehman Hashim Syed, a retired major in the Pakistani Army, for planning the attacks in association with Headley.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 15 January 2010, in a successful snatch operation, R&AW agents nabbed Sheikh Abdul Khwaja, one of the handlers of the 26/11 attacks, chief of HuJI India operations and a most wanted suspect in India, from Colombo, Sri Lanka, and brought him over to Hyderabad, India, for formal arrest.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 25 June 2012, the Delhi Police Department arrested Zabiuddin Ansari, alias Abu Hamza, one of the key suspects in the attack at the Indira Gandhi International Airport in New Delhi.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] His arrest was touted as the most significant development in the case since Kasab's arrest.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Security agencies had been chasing him for three years in Delhi.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Ansari is a LeT ultra and the Hindi tutor of the 10 attackers who were responsible for the Mumbai attacks in 2008.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] He was apprehended, after he was arrested and deported to India by Saudi Intelligence officials as per official request by Indian authorities.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] After Ansari's arrest, investigations revealed that in 2009 he allegedly stayed for a day in a room in Old Legislators's Hostel, belonging to Fauzia Khan, a former MLA and minister in Maharashtra government.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The minister, however, denied having any links with him.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Chidambaram asserted that Ansari was provided a safe place in Pakistan and was present in the control room, which could not have been established without active State support.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Ansari's interrogation further revealed that Sajid Mir and a Pakistani Army major visited India under fake names as cricket spectators to survey targets in Delhi and Mumbai for about a fortnight.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Sajid Mir, a Pakistani citizen and key operative of the militant Islamic extremist group LeT, is seen as one of the main organisers of the 2008 attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] He has been called the "mastermind" and "project manager".
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Federal Bureau of Investigation's Most Wanted list and the United States Department of State offers in its Rewards for Justice Program, a reward of up to $5 million for information leading to the arrest and conviction of Mir.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Mir has carried out terrorism operations in different parts of the world, including France.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On April 10, 2025, the NIA formally arrested Tahawwur Rana after his arrival from the U.S.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A total of 164 to 166 civilians and security personnel were killed in the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Among the dead were 26 foreign nationals from 14 countries.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Nine attackers were killed (and one captured).
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The deaths and injuries were due to bullet wounds and blast wounds.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A total of 38.5% of patients arriving at hospitals required surgery for bullet and shrapnel injuries.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Sir JJ Group of Hospitals treatment and postmortem data showed four died from postoperative septicemia.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A large majority of deaths and injuries were men.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The bodies of many of the dead hostages showed signs of torture or disfigurement.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A number of those killed were notable figures in business, media, and security services.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] This includes Gavriel Holtzberg, Andreas Liveras, Ralph Burkei, Loumia Hiridjee, and Sabina Sehgal Saikia.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The deputy chief minister of Maharashtra said that the terrorists planned to kill 5000 people.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Unexploded RDX was found near Taj Mahal Palace Hotel.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] According to compensation figures, 22 security personnel died in the attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Six security personnel were awarded the Ashok Chakra, India's highest peacetime military decoration.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Three railway officials of Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus were also killed.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The government of Maharashtra announced about ₹500,000 (US$5,200) as compensation to the kin of each of those killed in the terror attacks and about ₹50,000 (US$520) to the seriously injured.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The chief minister of Uttarakhand announced aid of ₹500,000 (US$5,200) to the family of NSG Commando Hawaldar Gajender Singh Bisht.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Free treatment was offered to the injured.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In August 2009, the Indian Hotels Company and the Oberoi Group received about US$28 million as part-payment of the insurance claims, on account of the attacks on Taj and Trident, from General Insurance Corporation of India.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attacks are sometimes referred to in India as "26/11", after the date in 2008 that the attacks began.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The Pradhan Inquiry Commission, appointed by the Maharashtra government, produced a report that was tabled before the legislative assembly more than a year after the events.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The report said the "war-like" attack was beyond the capacity to respond of any police force, but also found fault with the Mumbai Police Commissioner Hasan Gafoor's lack of leadership during the crisis.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The Maharashtra government planned to buy 36 speed boats to patrol the coastal areas and several helicopters for the same purpose, along with installation of surveillance cameras citywide.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] It also planned to create an anti-terror force called "Force One" and upgrade all the weapons that Mumbai police had prior to the attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The government strengthened anti-terror laws with UAPA 2008, and the federal National Investigation Agency was formed.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A Public Interest Litigation was filed by social activist Ketan Tirodkar to demand equal justice for all the police who were killed in the terror attack; especially for the members of the Bomb Disposal Squad of Mumbai Police.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] During the hearing of the petition, the government informed the High Court that the Union government of India rejected the proposal to award the Bomb Disposal Squad of the city police for their contribution in defusing grenades in the terror attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attacks also resulted in the suspension of peace talks between India and Pakistan, significantly increasing tensions between the two countries.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] India's then External Affairs Minister Pranab Mukherjee declared that India may indulge in military strikes against terror camps in Pakistan to protect its territorial integrity.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] There were also after-effects on the United States's relationships with both countries, the US-led NATO war in Afghanistan, and on the global war on terror.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] FBI chief Robert Mueller praised the "unprecedented cooperation" between American and Indian intelligence agencies over the Mumbai terror attack probe.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] However, Interpol secretary general Ronald Noble said that Indian intelligence agencies did not share any information with Interpol.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A new National Counter Terrorism Centre (NCTC) was proposed to be set up by the then-Home Minister P.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Chidambaram as an office to collect, collate, summarise, integrate, analyse, co-ordinate and report all information and inputs received from various intelligence agencies, state police departments, and other ministries and their departments.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attack led to an increase in anti-Pakistan sentiments across India, especially from right wing political groups, which continued in the aftermath.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Similar sentiments were echoed elsewhere, most notably in the United States of America, as 6 American citizens were killed in the attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Following the attack, as well as raid in Abbottabad in May 2011 that killed 9/11 mastermind Osama bin Laden, anti-Pakistan views and hate crimes against Pakistani origin people surged in the United States.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Consequently, due to such hate crimes and views, many Pakistanis and Pakistani-Americans have identified themselves as Indians to avoid discrimination and obtain jobs.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attacks caused a major economic loss to the city of Mumbai worth ₹40 billion ($818.33 million in 2008 exchange rates), as hotels, businesses, and shops were closed during that period, along with the temporary suspension of trading at the Bombay Stock Exchange.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In addition, insurance claims worth over ₹6 billion ($122 million) were settled, due to loss of lives and property damage caused by the terrorists.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attacks took place at a time, when the 2008 financial crisis caused major economic impact worldwide, despite India's economy being noted as second fastest growing during that period.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Pakistan moved troops towards the border with India voicing concerns about the Indian government's possible plans to launch attacks on Pakistani soil if it did not co-operate.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] After days of talks, the Pakistan government, however, decided to start moving troops away from the border.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Indians criticised their political leaders after the attacks, saying that their ineptness was partly responsible.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Patil for controversial reactions to the attack including taking the former's son and Bollywood director Ram Gopal Varma to tour the damaged Taj Hotel and the latter's remarks that the attacks were not a big deal in such a large city.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Indian Muslims condemned the attacks and refused to allow burial of the bodies of the attackers in their graveyards.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Groups of Muslims marched against the attacks and mosques observed silence.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Prominent Muslim personalities such as Bollywood actor Aamir Khan appealed to their community members in the country to observe Eid al-Adha as a day of mourning on 9 December.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The business establishment also reacted, with changes to transport, and requests for an increase in self-defence capabilities.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The attacks also triggered a chain of citizens' movements across India such as the India Today Group's "War Against Terror" campaign.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] There were vigils held across all of India with candles and placards commemorating the victims of the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The NSG commandos based in Delhi also met criticism for taking ten hours to reach the three sites under attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Additionally, anti-Pakistan protests took place in Mumbai and nationwide in the aftermath of the attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] During the protests, demonstrators shouted *Pakistan Murdabad* (meaning Down with Pakistan), and many demanding cutting any ties with Pakistan.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The sentiments against Pakistan surged after the attack in Mumbai, especially among Indian diaspora worldwide, and largely intensified after the 2019 Pulwama attack and the 2025 Pahalgam attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 28 December 2010, 2 years after the attack, UPA leader Digvijaya Singh was criticised for attending a book launch which described that the Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh had conspired the attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The book *RSS ki Saazish* (meaning Conspiracy by RSS), written by Aziz Burney, was extremely condemned by RSS members and opposition leaders.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Furthermore, the Congress party was also slammed for coining the terms of Hindu terrorists and Saffron terror, relating to several terror attacks across the nation before the November 2008 attack in Mumbai, most notably the bombings in Jaipur, Bangalore, Ahmedabad, and Delhi.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] International reaction for the attacks was widespread, with many countries and international organisations condemning the attacks and expressing their condolences to the civilian victims.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Many important personalities around the world also condemned the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Media coverage highlighted the use of social media and social networking tools, including Twitter and Flickr, in spreading information about the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] In addition, many Indian bloggers offered live textual coverage of the attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] A map of the attacks was set up by a web journalist using Google Maps.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] *The New York Times*, in July 2009, described the event as "what may be the most well-documented terrorist attack anywhere".
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] In November 2010, families of American victims of the attacks filed a lawsuit in Brooklyn, New York, naming Lt.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Ahmed Shuja Pasha, chief of the ISI, as being complicit in the Mumbai attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 22 September 2011, the attack on the American Embassy in Afghanistan was attributed to Pakistan via cell phone records identical to the attacks in Mumbai, also linked to Pakistan.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Several BJP leaders condemned the admission and accused the Congress party for being soft on Pakistan, commenting that the statement came too little, too late.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Kasab's trial was delayed due to legal issues, as many Indian lawyers were unwilling to represent him.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] A Mumbai Bar Association passed a resolution proclaiming that none of its members would represent Kasab.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] However, the Chief Justice of India stated that Kasab needed a lawyer for a fair trial.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] A lawyer for Kasab was eventually found, but was replaced due to a conflict of interest.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 25 February 2009, Indian investigators filed an 11,000-page chargesheet, formally charging Kasab with murder, conspiracy, and waging war against India among other charges.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Kasab's trial began on 23 March 2009, and he pled not guilty on 6 May 2009.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 10 June 2009, Devika Rotawan, a child who had been shot in her leg during the attack, identified Kasab as one of the attackers during her testimony.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The judge found many of the 86 charges were not addressed in his confession, and therefore the trial continued 23 July 2009.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Kasab initially apologised for the attacks and said he deserved the death penalty for his crimes, but on 18 December 2009, retracted his confession, and said he had been forced by police to make his confession.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Kasab was convicted of all 86 charges on 3 May 2010.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] He was found guilty of murder for directly killing seven people, conspiracy to commit murder for the deaths of the 164 people killed in the three-day terror siege, waging war against India, causing terror, and of conspiracy to murder two high-ranking police officers.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 6 May 2010, he was sentenced to death by hanging.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] However, he appealed his sentence at high court.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 21 February 2011, the Bombay High Court upheld the death sentence of Kasab, dismissing his appeal.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 29 August 2012, the Indian Supreme Court upheld the death sentence for Kasab.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The court stated, "We are left with no option but to award death penalty.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The primary and foremost offence committed by Kasab is waging war against the government of India".
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The verdict followed 10 weeks of appeal hearings, and was decided by a two-judge Supreme Court panel, which was led by Judge Aftab Alam.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The panel rejected arguments that Kasab was denied a free and fair trial.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Kasab filed a mercy petition with the President of India, which was rejected on 5 November.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On November 21, 2012, at 7:30 AM, Kasab was hanged in Pune's Yerwada jail.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The Indian embassy in Islamabad informed the Pakistani government of Kasab's hanging via letter.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Pakistan refused to take the letter, which was then faxed to them.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] His family in Pakistan was sent news of his hanging via a courier.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Zabiuddin Ansari, also known as Abu Hamza, a radicalized Indian national working for the Lashkar-e-Taiba, who was extradited from Saudi Arabia in June 2012, was interrogated by authorities in India on his role in the attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] While he revealed that the plot was planned for 2006 using Indian youth, the huge cache of arms and ammunition to be used for the attacks were seized in Aurangabad.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 2 August 2016, he was sentenced to life imprisonment in relation to the arms haul case by the special MCOCA court.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Indian and Pakistani police exchanged DNA evidence, photographs and items found with the attackers to piece together a detailed portrait of the Mumbai plot.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Police in Pakistan arrested seven people, including Hammad Amin Sadiq, a homoeopathic pharmacist, who arranged bank accounts and secured supplies.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Sadiq and six others began their formal trial on 3 October 2009 in Pakistan.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Indian authorities said the prosecution stopped well short of top Lashkar leaders.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] In November 2009, Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh said that Pakistan had not done enough to bring the perpetrators of the attacks to justice.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] An eight-member commission comprising defence lawyers, prosecutors and a court official was allowed to travel to India on 15 March 2013 to gather evidence for the prosecution of seven suspects linked to the 2008 Mumbai attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] However, the defence lawyers were barred from cross-examining the four prosecution witnesses in the case including Ajmal Kasab.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On the eve of the first anniversary of 26/11, a Pakistani anti-terror court formally charged seven accused, including LeT operations commander Zaki ur Rehman Lakhvi.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] However, the actual trial started on 5 May 2012.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The Pakistani court conducting trial of Mumbai attacks accused, reserved its judgement on the application filed by Lakhvi, challenging the report of the judicial panel, to 17 July 2012.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 17 July 2012, the court refused to take the findings of the Pakistani judicial commission as part of the evidence.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] However, it ruled that if a new agreement, which allows the panel's examination of witnesses, is reached, the prosecution may make an application for sending the panel to Mumbai.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The Indian government, upset over the court ruling, however, contended that evidence collected by the Pakistani judicial panel has evidential value to punish all those involved in the attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 21 September 2013, a Pakistani judicial commission arrived in India to carry out the investigation and to cross examine the witnesses.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] This is the second such visit: the one in March 2012 was not a success as its report was rejected by an anti-terrorism court in Pakistan due to lack of evidence.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Saeed was sentenced to serve 15 years in December 2020 on several charges of terror financing, which was extended to 31 years in April 2022.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The following month, on 2 January 2021, Zakiur Rehman Lakhvi, another mastermind of the attack, was arrested on the same charges of terror financing, and handed a 15-year sentence.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 24 June 2022, Sajid Mir, the co-plotter of the attack and a Pakistan Army Officer, was sentenced to 15 years for terror financing.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Mir was earlier declared dead and Pakistan had denied his presence, but due to compliance of FATF actions, Pakistan was forced to admit about his existence.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] An interrogation with Sayed Zabiuddin Ansari revealed that Mir scouted targets in 2005 with a fake name and passport under the cricket diplomacy to watch the India-Pakistan ODI Cricket match at Mohali.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Additionally, Ansari stated that after visiting several places in India, Mir prepared the Taj Hotel's miniature model to familiarise the attackers with the hotel.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Mir was reportedly poisoned in prison in December 2023.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Following the conviction of Mir, Lakhvi and Saeed, the Financial Action Task Force removed Pakistan from the greylist in October 2022.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 15 November 2024, 11 days before the 16th anniversary of the attack, a video verified through facial recognition revealed about co-conspirator Zakiur Rehman Lakhvi participating in a fitness test, which questioned about Pakistan's compliance with international sanctions from the FATF.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Despite his conviction, Lakhvi was reported to move freely in Lahore, Rawalpindi, and Okara.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] India Today's intelligence sources described his arrest as a pseudo-event and cover-up, with no genuine enforcement of restrictions and pretense on seriousness to tackle terrorism.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 10 June 2011, Tahawwur Rana was acquitted of plotting the 2008 Mumbai attacks but was held guilty on two other charges.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] He was sentenced to 14 years in federal prison on 17 January 2013.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] In May 2023, a US court approved his extradition to India where he is sought for his involvement in the 2008 Mumbai terror attacks.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] David Headley pleaded guilty to 12 counts related to the attacks, including conspiracy to commit murder in India and aiding and abetting in the murder of six Americans.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 23 January 2013, he was sentenced to 35 years in federal prison.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] His plea that he not be extradited to India, Pakistan or Denmark was accepted.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 13 February 2025, US President Donald Trump confirmed the extradition of Rana to India, which was confirmed by the Supreme Court of the United States in May 2023, after the government of India renewed its request for his extradition.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On 8 April 2025, after Rana's last plea to stop his extradition was rejected by the Supreme Court of the United States, a team of National Investigation Agency officers arrived in the United States to take Rana into custody.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On the first anniversary of the event, the state paid homage to the victims of the attack.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Force One—a new security force created by the Maharashtra government—staged a parade from Nariman Point to Chowpatty.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Other memorials and candlelight vigils were also organised at the various locations where the attacks occurred.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On the second anniversary of the event, homage was again paid to the victims.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] On the 10th anniversary of the 26/11 Mumbai terror attacks, Nariman House, one of the several establishments that were targeted by the Lashkar-e-Taiba terrorists, were to be declared a memorial and renamed as Nariman Light House.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The Indian Express group hosts an annual memorial event, 26/11 – Stories of Strength, in Mumbai to pay homage to those killed in the ghastly terror attacks in the city in 2008.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] The memorial event started in 2016, is now organised at the Gateway of India and brings forth the inspiring stories of courage and strength of more than 100 survivors that the Indian Express has interviewed over the past decade.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] Actor Amitabh Bachchan has been the brand ambassador for the event over the years.
[src:cricket/2008-mumbai-attacks-p02] In his speech, Khan also paid tribute to the security personnel who were martyred in the attacks, while stating that when peace prevails, nothing can shake or defeat India, or break the spirit of its people.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] On 3 March 2009, a bus carrying Sri Lankan cricketers, part of a larger convoy, was fired upon by 12 gunmen near Gaddafi Stadium in Lahore, Pakistan.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The cricketers were on their way to play the third day of the second Test against the Pakistani cricket team.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Six members of the Sri Lanka national cricket team were wounded and six Pakistani policemen and two civilians were killed.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The attack was believed to have been carried out by the Lashkar-e-Jhangvi.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] In August 2016, three of the terrorists involved in the attack were killed during a police raid in Lahore.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] In October, the attack's mastermind was killed in eastern Afghanistan during a military operation, while hiding there.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The safety of touring cricket teams in Pakistan had long been an issue.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] In May 2002, New Zealand abandoned their Test series in Pakistan after a suicide bomb attack outside their hotel.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] However, they returned in the 2003/2004 season to fulfill their commitments.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Australia had refused to tour in October 2002 on safety grounds.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The Sri Lankan cricket team was in Pakistan as a replacement for the Indian team, who had pulled out after the terrorist attacks in Mumbai.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] In order to persuade the Sri Lankan team to visit, the Pakistan government offered to give them presidential-style security, which they failed to provide to the Sri Lankan team.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The series was the first Test tour of Pakistan since South Africa visited in October 2007.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] According to the officials, 12 gunmen were hiding near Liberty Square, in the centre of Lahore, waiting for the Sri Lankan team to pass on their way to the Gaddafi stadium.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] They started firing at the bus when it crossed the road.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The Pakistan police escorting the team returned fire; in the ensuing fighting, six policemen and two civilians died.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] After about 20 minutes, the militants fled, leaving behind rocket launchers and grenades.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The gunmen first shot at the wheels of the bus, and then fired at the bus itself and its occupants.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The attackers had fired a rocket at the bus, which missed and hit a nearby electric pole.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The driver of the bus, Mehar Mohammad Khalil, had then kept on driving a distance of about 500 metres (1,600 ft) until they reached the stadium.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Khalil was awarded Tamgha-i-Shujaat for his bravery.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The attackers had also thrown a grenade under the bus, which exploded after the bus had passed over it.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] A minivan following the team bus carrying the match referee and umpires was also fired upon and the driver was killed.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Simon Taufel, Steve Davis, Nadeem Ghauri, Ahsan Raza, umpires performance manager Peter Manuel, liaison officer Abdul Sami and ICC match referee Chris Broad were in this minivan.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The minivan was subsequently allegedly abandoned by security personnel and no bullets were fired by the security forces for twenty minutes.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Chris Broad threw himself over and kept his hand on the chest of Ahsan Raza to slow down the profuse bleeding from a bullet injury.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] A police officer who climbed into the minivan to seek cover drove the minivan to safety.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Security cameras captured footage of several gunmen carrying automatic weapons and backpacks, firing on the convoy from the Liberty Square roundabout.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] They were later seen jogging up the street and escaping on motorcycles.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The video was broadcast around the world presenting pictures of the attacks.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] They arrived at 8:39 am local time and left at 8:46 am.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The attackers were armed with AK-47 assault rifles, hand grenades, RPG launchers, claymores and explosive charges.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The Sri Lankan team were then taken to the stadium and airlifted from the pitch via Pakistan Air Force Mil Mi-17 helicopters, and immediate arrangements were made for the Sri Lankan team to return to Colombo on the next available flight.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The second Test, which was the last scheduled fixture of the tour, was abandoned as a draw.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Six Pakistani policemen and two civilians were killed in the attack.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Samaraweera and Paranavitana were hospitalised following the incident.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The others had sustained minor injuries and shrapnel wounds.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Samaraweera sustained shrapnel wounds to his thigh, and Paranavitana to his chest.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The team's Assistant Coach Paul Farbrace was also injured.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Although it was reported that Coach Trevor Bayliss also sustained minor injuries, it was later announced that this was incorrect.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Reserve umpire Ahsan Raza, who was travelling in a van for the umpires that was following the Sri Lankan team bus, was shot twice and taken to hospital.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The driver of the minibus was killed in the attack.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Immediately following the attacks, Pakistani authorities blamed the Lashkar-e-Taiba (LeT), a militant organisation.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Pakistani officials said that the attacks were similar to the Mumbai attacks.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Most of the Pakistani press blamed Pakistani Islamist militants and Al-Qaeda for the attacks.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Police said that kidnapping was a possible motive, but police officials refused to comment on this.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Sri Lankan Foreign Minister Rohitha Bogollagama said on 4 March that he could not rule out involvement of the rebel Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) in the Lahore attacks.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Some European intelligence sources supported this suspicion.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Sri Lankan military officials, on the other hand, were skeptical of LTTE involvement, and an LTTE spokesperson labelled reports of LTTE connection as 'not true'.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] A junior Pakistani cabinet minister said that the government had evidence that the attackers came from India.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] On 6 March 2009, government officials had ruled out the involvement of Indian intelligence agency Research and Analysis Wing and LTTE and were zeroing in on Lashkar-e-Taiba.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] On the morning of the attack, the Sri Lankan and Pakistani cricket teams did not depart from the hotel together, as they had done on previous days, and the Pakistani team's schedule was delayed by 5 minutes.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Statements by Australian umpire Simon Taufel, match referee Chris Broad, and spin bowler Muttiah Muralitharan, referencing this delay sparked conspiracy theories that the militants were acting on inside information.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Later, Muralitharan expressed alarm at such interpretations of his comments and explained that he only suspected the gunmen to be monitoring the team movements.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Federal Bureau of Investigation director Robert Mueller arrived in Pakistan the day after these attacks and met with Pakistani officials to discuss security issues and the Mumbai attacks.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Interior Adviser Rehman Malik, told the National Assembly Standing Committee on the Interior that no evidence of LeT's involvement has been found so far, and that sufficient evidence has been surfaced pointing to involvement of a foreign hand.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The Investigation committee found three Superintendents of police (SPs) to have neglected the initial warning. by Intelligence agencies The Chief Minister of Punjab had also tipped off the authorities about a possible threat to the Sri Lankan team a month before.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] On 5 March, Salmaan Taseer, the governor of Punjab province, said the individuals responsible for the attack had been identified, but would not be revealed until the investigation was complete.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The province offered a reward of 10 million rupees (US$125,000) for information leading to the capture of the militants responsible for the attack.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Police in Punjab arrested over 250 suspects, including 4 who were said to be 'prime suspects'.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Police called Muhammad Aqeel, who ran a sports bikes business in Islampura, the mastermind behind the attack, and said that he had received a call from one of the militants at 9:05 am on the morning of the attacks asking for instructions.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Though Aqeel was still absconding, his brother, Muhammad Faisal, had been arrested.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Police also arrested Shahzad Babar of Rahim Yar Khan after a Subscriber Identity Module (SIM) card registered in his name was used in the attack along with eight others.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Security officials in Pakistan told The Times that most of the two dozen people arrested in connection with the attacks belonged to Jaish-e-Mohammed, Lashkar-e-Jhangvi, outlawed militant groups with close links to Al-Qaeda.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Aqeel, who is an activist of Lashkar-e-Jhangvi, escaped a police raid on his home in Kahuta on 9 March 2009.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Also another gunman Zubair, aka Naik Mohammad, of Zubair, was arrested from Madina Colony, Walton Road in Lahore.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] He was a waiter at a hotel in Rawalpindi, when he was recruited by Sifullah.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] He went to Miram Shah and was trained in the use of different weapons.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Other accused including Samiullah, alias Ejaz of Nankana district, Adnan, alias Sajjad, Ajmal alias Ahsaan, Farooq, Ameer of Punjab Taliban, and Umer, alias Abdul Wahab of D.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The attack was planned at Tauheed Hotel, and a house rented for this purpose in Madina Colony, Walton Road.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The auto rickshaws used in the attack were purchased by Samiullah.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] A secret investigative report has surfaced later prepared by the Additional Inspector General of the Crime Investigation Division, Punjab on 22 January 2009 outlining the potential threat to the Sri Lankan team.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Pakistan – The attack was condemned by the Pakistani president Asif Ali Zardari and prime minister Yousaf Raza Gillani.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Governor Salmaan Taseer stated that the same people who executed the 2008 Mumbai attacks were responsible for this attack.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Following the attack, Pakistan's interior minister Rehman Malik declared Pakistan to be "in a state of war".
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Pakistani officials also blamed India of covert involvement, citing long-standing enmity between the two South Asian countries.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] These claims were largely seen as an exercise in diverting attention away from the crisis.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Chief Minister of Punjab (Pakistan) Shehbaz Sharif criticised the current government and said that he had already tipped authorities of a possible attack beforehand.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Pakistani newspaper *Dawn* condemned the attack and cited security loopholes.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The *Daily Times*, blamed Al-Qaeda and the Lashkar-e Jhangvi in an editorial, stating, "International cricket is no longer possible in Pakistan; therefore we should stop accusing foreign teams of discriminating against Pakistan vis-à-vis India.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The paper goes on to say that "their candid comments will seal the fate of Pakistan cricket for some time to come".
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] It also said that Pakistan "must give up complaining" and that "ways to liven up the game at the domestic level need to be reconsidered with renewed urgency".
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Sri Lanka – Sri Lankan president Mahinda Rajapaksa said, "I condemn this cowardly terrorist attack targeting the Sri Lankan cricket team.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The Sri Lankan team praised the bus driver.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Then-captain of the Sri Lanka cricket team Mahela Jayawardene praised Khalil saying he owed his life to the driver.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Spinner Muttiah Muralitharan also gave Khalil his team shirt.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] United Nations – Secretary General Ban Ki-moon strongly condemned the attacks according to UN spokesman Marie Okabe.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The West Indies Cricket Board made a statement through president Julian Hunte and said "It was a sad day for International Cricket", and gave their full sympathy to the Sri Lankan players and the umpires.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Indian and New Zealand players wore black armbands while playing their next One Day International as a show of solidarity towards the Sri Lankan players injured in the attack, as did Australia and South Africa while playing their next test.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Australia – Prime Minister Kevin Rudd also condemned the attack on the Sri Lankan cricket team, calling it "shameful and cowardly".
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] He demanded answers from Pakistan after claims that police left Australians travelling with Sri Lanka's cricket team in the lurch as the bus was attacked.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] China – Foreign Ministry spokesman Qin Gang said that the Chinese government expressed deep condolences to the victims and sincere sympathy to the wounded.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] France – French Ministry of Foreign and European Affairs expressed solidarity with the Pakistani people and authorities at this "testing time".
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Chidambaram expressed shock over the attack on the Sri Lankan cricket team in Pakistan: "We condemn the incident.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] We are shocked by that incident." Further he said that Pakistan could become a failed state and it was not clear who was in control of the country.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] New Zealand - Prime Minister John Key was outraged over the attack.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] He called it a "despicable terrorist act" while condemning the attack.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] He further said that he intends to convey "a message of condolence to the Sri Lankan Government and Sri Lankan cricket team".
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Turkey – Foreign Minister Ali Babacan called Pakistan's Foreign Minister Makhdoom Shah Mehmood Qureshi and offered his condolences personally and on behalf of the government and the people of Turkey.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Foreign Secretary David Miliband stated that Pakistan was facing a "mortal threat" from internal militancy.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] United States – President Barack Obama expressed deep concern over the attack.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Secretary of State Hillary Clinton called these attacks an "eerie replica" of the Mumbai attacks and said Pakistan was facing a serious internal security threat.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Ambassador to Afghanistan Christopher Dell mused that Pakistan potentially posed a bigger security problem for the rest of the world than Afghanistan.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Politician and former Pakistan cricket captain Imran Khan criticised the security arrangements and said that the security provided was 10 times less than what is provided to government officials such as Rehman Malik.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Match referee Chris Broad was also critical of the security provided.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] He stated that he and his colleagues were left like 'sitting ducks' in the trailing minivan during the attack.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] He also accused the security personnel of fleeing the scene.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] He questioned why the Pakistan team which usually travelled with the Sri Lankan team was delayed by seven minutes that day and avoided being attacked.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Javed Miandad was critical of Broad's comments and demanded that International Cricket Council ban him for life.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Pakistan Cricket Board lodged a formal complaint against Chris Broad with the International Cricket Council on 9 March 2009.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Ijaz Butt, the head of Pakistan Cricket Board accused Broad of lying.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Umpire Simon Taufel also said that the umpire's minibus was abandoned while the players' bus was moved to the ground to evacuate the players.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Criticising the security entourage for abandoning them and inability of the police to arrest the attackers Simon said, "You tell me why no one was caught.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Co-umpire Steve Davis said "he felt let down" by the security.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] International Cricket Council umpires performance manager for East Asia, Sri Lanka and Pakistan, Peter Manuel told *Dawn* that the minivan carrying the umpires was basically abandoned by the security personnel: "It was unbelievable.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Bullets were raining on us and not a shot was fired in our defense by the Pakistan security officials." Sri Lanka coach Trevor Bayliss backed the comments made by Simon Taufel, Chris Broad and Steve Davis criticising the security.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Intikhab Alab, Pakistan cricket team's coach, asked Chris Broad to apologise to his country and team due to the remarks he made against Pakistani police security.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] English cricketer Dominic Cork who was commentating in Pakistan on the series and who himself was caught in the attack later criticised the security and Pakistan Cricket Board chairman Ijaz Butt.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Sri Lankan bowler Muttiah Muralitharan said the security arrangement was the worst he had ever seen, and vastly inferior to that provided in Sri Lanka.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] He said "The security people we had didn't even seem to fight back.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Were they professionals with enough training?
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] I was surprised the terrorists were able to just reload the magazines and keep firing, and they never got caught.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Eyewitness Habib Akram, bureau chief of SAMAA TV news channel, said that the gunmen were very calm as they moved and fired by turns and that there was hardly any fire returned by the police.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] His office overlooks the traffic circle where the incident took place.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Closed-circuit television footage of the event reported by Geo TV showed four of the attackers walking or jogging away unchallenged from the site, into a marketplace while no policemen are seen.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Insurance cost for cricket matches in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Sri Lanka rose.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The New Zealand team cancelled its December 2009 tour of Pakistan.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Bangladesh also put off a scheduled tour by Pakistan to Bangladesh.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The elections were slated to be held between 16 April and 13 May and it was impossible to reschedule them while IPL organisers appeared to be unwilling to postpone the tournament.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Former England coach Duncan Fletcher said that English players contracted to the IPL would now be more concerned for their safety.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The 2009 Indian Premier League was hosted by South Africa between 18 April and 24 May 2009.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Former Indian captain Sourav Ganguly said after these attacks Pakistan was not a safe venue to play cricket.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The 2011 Cricket World Cup was to be co-hosted by Pakistan, India, Sri Lanka and Bangladesh, but in the wake of this attack on the Sri Lankan cricket team the International Cricket Council (ICC) stripped Pakistan of its hosting rights due to security concerns.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The headquarters of the organising committee were originally situated in Lahore, but was then shifted to Mumbai.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Pakistan was supposed to hold 14 matches, including one semi-final.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Eight of Pakistan's matches were awarded to India, four to Sri Lanka and two to Bangladesh.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] The Sri Lankan Foreign minister has said the Sri Lankan cricket team "will give highest consideration to the invitation extended to it to undertake visit again.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] Sri Lanka will not allow Pakistan's isolation in cricket." In October 2017, the Sri Lankan cricket team returned to Pakistan for the first time since the attack to play a Twenty20 International match at the Gaddafi Stadium.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] In September 2019, the Sri Lankan team toured Pakistan, playing a 3-match One-Day International series in National Stadium, Karachi and a 3-match Twenty20 International series in Gaddafi Stadium, Lahore.
[src:cricket/2009-attack-on-the-sri-lanka-national-cricket-team] In December 2019, Sri Lanka agreed to play two match test series in Pakistan, thus marking test cricket's return to Pakistan after a decade since the terror attack.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The fielding team aims to prevent runs by dismissing batters (so they are "out").
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] When ten batters have been dismissed, the innings (playing phase) ends and the teams swap roles.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Traditionally, cricketers play in all-white kit, but in limited overs cricket, they wear club or team colours.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In addition to the basic kit, some players wear protective gear to prevent injury caused by the ball, which is a hard, solid spheroid made of compressed leather with a slightly raised sewn seam enclosing a cork core layered with tightly wound string.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The earliest known definite reference to cricket is to it being played in South East England in the mid-16th century.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] It spread globally with the expansion of the British Empire, with the first international matches in the second half of the 19th century.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The game's governing body is the International Cricket Council (ICC), which has over 100 members, twelve of which are full members who play Test matches.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The game's rules, the *Laws of Cricket*, are maintained by Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) in London.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The sport is primarily played in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Afghanistan, Australia, New Zealand, England and Wales, South Africa and the West Indies.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] While cricket has traditionally been played largely by men, women's cricket has experienced significant growth in the 21st century.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The most successful side playing international cricket is Australia, which has won eight One Day International trophies, including six World Cups, more than any other country, and has been the top-rated Test side more than any other country.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Cricket is one of many games in the "club ball" sphere that involve hitting a ball with a hand-held implement.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Others include baseball (which shares many similarities with cricket, both belonging in the more specific bat-and-ball games category), golf, hockey, tennis, squash, badminton and table tennis.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In cricket's case, a key difference is the existence of a solid target structure, the wicket (originally, it is thought, a "wicket gate" through which sheep were herded), that the batter must defend.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] It is generally believed that cricket originated as a children's game in the south-eastern counties of England, sometime during the medieval period.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Although there are claims for prior dates, the earliest definite reference to cricket being played comes from evidence given at a court case in Guildford in January 1597 (Old Style, equating to January 1598 in the modern calendar).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Given Derrick's age, it was about half a century earlier when he was at school, and so it is certain that cricket was being played c.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The view that it was originally a children's game is reinforced by Randle Cotgrave's 1611 English-French dictionary in which he defined the noun "*crosse*" as "the crooked staff wherewith boys play at cricket", and the verb form "*crosser*" as "to play at cricket".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] One possible source for the sport's name is the Old English word "*cryce*" (or "*cricc*") meaning a crutch or staff.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In Samuel Johnson's *Dictionary*, he derived cricket from "*cryce*, Saxon, a stick".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In Old French, the word "*criquet*" seems to have meant a kind of club or stick.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Given the strong medieval trade connections between south-east England and the County of Flanders when the latter belonged to the Duchy of Burgundy, the name may have been derived from the Middle Dutch (in use in Flanders at the time) "*krick*"(*-e*), meaning a stick (crook).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Another possible source is the Middle Dutch word "*krickstoel*", meaning a long low stool used for kneeling in church that resembled the long low wicket with two stumps used in early cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] According to Heiner Gillmeister, a European language expert of Bonn University, "cricket" derives from the Middle Dutch phrase for hockey, "*met de (krik ket)sen*" ("with the stick chase").
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Gillmeister has suggested that not only the name but also the sport itself may be of Flemish origin.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Although the main object of the game has always been to score the most runs, the early form of cricket differed from the modern game in certain key technical aspects; the North American variant of cricket known as wicket retained many of these aspects.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The ball was bowled underarm by the bowler and along the ground towards a batter armed with a bat that in shape resembled a hockey stick; the batter defended a low, two-stump wicket; and runs were called notches because the scorers recorded them by notching tally sticks.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In 1611, the year Cotgrave's dictionary was published, ecclesiastical court records at Sidlesham in Sussex state that two parishioners, Bartholomew Wyatt and Richard Latter, failed to attend church on Easter Sunday because they were playing cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] They were fined 12d each and ordered to do penance.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] This is the earliest mention of adult participation in cricket and it was around the same time that the earliest known organised inter-parish or village match was played, at Chevening, Kent.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In 1624, a player called Jasper Vinall died after he was accidentally struck on the head during a match between two parish teams in Sussex.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Cricket remained a low-key local pursuit for much of the 17th century.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] It is known, through numerous references found in the records of ecclesiastical court cases, to have been proscribed at times by the Puritans before and during the Commonwealth.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The problem was nearly always the issue of Sunday play, as the Puritans considered cricket to be "profane" if played on the Sabbath, especially if large crowds or gambling were involved.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] According to the social historian Derek Birley, there was a "great upsurge of sport after the Restoration" in 1660.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Several members of the court of King Charles II took a strong interest in cricket during that era.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Gambling on sport became a problem significant enough for Parliament to pass the 1664 Gambling Act, limiting stakes to £100, which was, in any case, a colossal sum exceeding the annual income of 99% of the population.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Along with horse racing, as well as prizefighting and other types of blood sport, cricket was perceived to be a gambling sport.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Rich patrons made matches for high stakes, forming teams in which they engaged the first professional players.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] By the end of the century, cricket had developed into a major sport that was spreading throughout England and was already being taken abroad by English mariners and colonisers—the earliest reference to cricket overseas is dated 1676.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] A 1697 newspaper report survives of "a great cricket match" played in Sussex "for fifty guineas apiece", the earliest known contest that is generally considered a First Class match.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The patrons and other players from the gentry began to classify themselves as "amateurs" to establish a clear distinction from the professionals, who were invariably members of the working class, even to the point of having separate changing and dining facilities.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In time, a perception took hold that the typical amateur who played in first-class cricket, until 1962 when amateurism was abolished, was someone with a public school education who had then gone to one of Cambridge or Oxford University.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Society insisted that such people were "officers and gentlemen" whose destiny was to provide leadership.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The game underwent major development in the 18th century to become England's national sport.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Its success was underwritten by the twin necessities of patronage and betting.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Cricket was prominent in London as early as 1707 and, in the middle years of the century, large crowds flocked to matches on the Artillery Ground in Finsbury.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The single wicket form of the sport attracted huge crowds and wagers to match, its popularity peaking in the 1748 season.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Bowling underwent an evolution around 1760 when bowlers began to pitch (bounce) the ball instead of rolling or skimming it towards the batter.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] This caused a revolution in bat design because, to deal with the bouncing ball, it was necessary to introduce the modern straight bat in place of the old "hockey stick" shape.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The Hambledon Club was founded in the 1760s and, for the next twenty years until the formation of Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) and the opening of Lord's Old Ground in 1787, Hambledon was both the game's greatest club and its focal point.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] MCC quickly became the sport's premier club and the custodian of the *Laws of Cricket*.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] New Laws introduced in the latter part of the 18th century include the three-stump wicket and leg before wicket (lbw).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The 19th century saw underarm bowling superseded by first roundarm and then overarm bowling.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Organisation of the game at county level led to the creation of the county clubs, starting with Sussex in 1839.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In December 1889, the eight leading county clubs formed the official County Championship, which began in 1890.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The most famous player of the 19th century was W.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Grace, who started his long and influential career in 1865.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] It was especially during the career of Grace that the distinction between amateurs and professionals became blurred by the existence of players like him who were nominally amateur but, in terms of their financial gain, *de facto* professional.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Grace himself was said to have been paid more money for playing cricket than any professional.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The last two decades before the First World War have been called the "Golden Age of cricket".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] It is a nostalgic name prompted by the collective sense of loss resulting from the war, but the period did produce some great players and memorable matches, especially as organised competition at county and Test level developed.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Meanwhile, the British Empire had been instrumental in spreading the game overseas, and by the middle of the 19th century it had become well established in Australia, the Caribbean, British India (which also includes present-day Pakistan and Bangladesh), New Zealand, North America and South Africa.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In 1844, the first international match took place between what were essentially club teams, from the United States and Canada, in New York; Canada won.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In 1859, a team of English players went to North America on the first overseas tour.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In 1862, an English team made the first tour of Australia.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The first Australian team to travel overseas consisted of Aboriginal stockmen who toured England in 1868.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In 1876–77, an England team took part in what was retrospectively recognised as the first-ever Test match at the Melbourne Cricket Ground against Australia.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The rivalry between England and Australia gave birth to The Ashes in 1882, which remains Test cricket's most famous contest.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Test cricket began to expand in 1888–89 when South Africa played England.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The inter-war years were dominated by Australia's Don Bradman, statistically the greatest Test batter of all time.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] To curb his dominance, England employed bodyline tactics during the 1932–33 Ashes series.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] These involved bowling at the body of the batter and setting a field, resulting in batters having to choose between being hit or risk getting out.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] This series moved cricket from a game to a matter of national importance, with diplomatic cables being passed between the two countries over the incident.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] During this time, the number of Test nations continued to grow, with the West Indies, New Zealand and India being admitted as full Test members within a four-year period from 1928 to 1932.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] An enforced break during the Second World War stopped Test Cricket for a time, although the Partition of India caused Pakistan to gain Test status in 1952.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] As teams began to travel more, the game quickly grew from 500 tests in 84 years to 1000 within the next 23.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Cricket entered a new era in 1963 when English counties introduced the limited overs variant.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] As it was sure to produce a result, limited overs cricket was lucrative, and the number of matches increased.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The first Limited Overs International was played in 1971, and the governing International Cricket Council (ICC), seeing its potential, staged the first limited overs Cricket World Cup in 1975.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Meanwhile, South Africa was banned by the ICC due to apartheid from 1970 until 1992.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] 1992 also brought about the introduction of the Zimbabwe team.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The 21st century brought with it the Bangladesh Team, who made their Test debut in 2000.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The game itself also grew, with a new format made up of 20-over innings being created.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] This format, called T20 cricket, quickly became a highly popular format, putting the longer formats at risk.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The new shorter format also introduced franchise cricket, with new tournaments like the Indian Premier League and the Australian Big Bash League.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The ICC has selected the T20 format as cricket's growth format, and has introduced a T20 World Cup which is played every two years; T20 cricket has also been increasingly accepted into major events such as the Asian Games.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The resultant growth has seen cricket's fanbase cross one billion people, with 90% of them in South Asia.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] T20's success has also spawned even shorter formats, such as 10-over cricket (T10) and 100-ball cricket, though not without controversy.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Outside factors have also taken their toll on cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] For example, the 2008 Mumbai attacks led India and Pakistan to suspend their bilateral series indefinitely.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The 2009 attack on the Sri Lankan team during their tour of Pakistan led to Pakistan being unable to host matches until 2019.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In 2017, Afghanistan and Ireland became the 11th and 12th Test nations.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In cricket, the rules of the game are codified in *The Laws of Cricket* (hereinafter called "the Laws"), which has a global remit.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] There are 42 Laws (always written with a capital "L").
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The earliest known version of the code was drafted in 1744, and since 1788, it has been owned and maintained by its custodian, the Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) in London.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Cricket is a bat-and-ball game played on a cricket field (see image of cricket pitch and creases) between two teams of eleven players each.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The field is usually circular or oval in shape, and the edge of the playing area is marked by a boundary, which may be a fence, part of the stands, a rope, a painted line, or a combination of these; the boundary must if possible be marked along its entire length.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In the approximate centre of the field is a rectangular pitch (see image, below) on which a wooden target called a wicket is sited at each end; the wickets are placed 22 yards (20 m) apart.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The pitch is a flat surface 10 feet (3.0 m) wide, with very short grass that tends to be worn away as the game progresses (cricket can also be played on artificial surfaces, notably matting).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Each wicket is made of three wooden stumps topped by two bails.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] As illustrated, the pitch is marked at each end with four white painted lines: a bowling crease, a popping crease and two return creases.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The three stumps are aligned centrally on the bowling crease, which is eight feet eight inches long.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The popping crease is drawn four feet in front of the bowling crease and parallel to it; although it is drawn as a 12 ft (3.7 m) line (six feet on either side of the wicket), it is, in fact, unlimited in length.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The return creases are drawn at right angles to the popping crease so that they intersect the ends of the bowling crease; each return crease is drawn as an 8 ft (2.4 m) line, so that it extends four feet behind the bowling crease, but is also, in fact, unlimited in length.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Before a match begins, the team captains (who are also players) toss a coin to decide which team will bat first and so take the first innings.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] "Innings" is the term used for each phase of play in the match.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In each innings, one team bats, attempting to score runs, while the other team bowls and fields the ball, attempting to restrict the scoring and dismiss the batters.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] When the first innings ends, the teams change roles; there can be two to four innings depending upon the type of match.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] A match with four scheduled innings is played over three to five days; a match with two scheduled innings is usually completed in a single day.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] During an innings, all eleven members of the fielding team take the field, but usually only two members of the batting team are on the field at any given time.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The order of batters is usually announced just before the match, but it can be varied.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The wicket-keeper (a specialised fielder behind the batter) and the batters wear protective gear because of the hardness of the ball, which can be delivered at speeds of more than 145 kilometres per hour (90 mph) and presents a major health and safety concern.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Protective clothing includes pads (designed to protect the knees and shins), batting gloves or wicket-keeper's gloves for the hands, a safety helmet for the head, and a box for male players inside the trousers (to protect the crotch area).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Some batters wear additional padding inside their shirts and trousers such as thigh pads, arm pads, rib protectors and shoulder pads.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The only fielders allowed to wear protective gear are those in positions very close to the batter (i.e., if they are alongside or in front of him), but they cannot wear gloves or external leg guards.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Subject to certain variations, on-field clothing generally includes a collared shirt with short or long sleeves; long trousers; woolen pullover (if needed); cricket cap (for fielding) or a safety helmet; and spiked shoes or boots to increase traction.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The kit is traditionally all white, and this remains the case in Test and first-class cricket, but in limited overs cricket, team colours are now worn instead.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] White balls are mainly used in limited overs cricket, especially in matches played at night, under floodlights (left). ii) A new red ball.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Red balls are used in day Test cricket, first-class cricket and some other forms of cricket (center).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The essence of the sport is that a bowler delivers (i.e., bowls) the ball from their end of the pitch towards the batter who, armed with a bat, is "on strike" at the other end (see next sub-section: *Basic gameplay*).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The bat is made of wood, usually *Salix alba* (white willow), and has the shape of a blade topped by a cylindrical handle.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The blade must not be more than 4.25 inches (10.8 cm) wide and the total length of the bat not more than 38 inches (97 cm).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] There is no standard for the weight, which is usually between 2 lb 7 oz and 3 lb (1.1 and 1.4 kg).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The ball is a hard leather-seamed spheroid, with a circumference of 9 inches (23 cm).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The ball has a "seam": six rows of stitches attaching the leather shell of the ball to the string and cork interior.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The seam on a new ball is prominent and helps the bowler propel it in a less predictable manner.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] During matches, the quality of the ball deteriorates to a point where it is no longer usable; during the course of this deterioration, its behaviour in flight will change and can influence the outcome of the match.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Players will, therefore, attempt to modify the ball's behaviour by modifying its physical properties.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Polishing the ball and wetting it with sweat or saliva was legal, even when the polishing was deliberately done on one side only to increase the ball's swing through the air.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The use of saliva has since been made illegal due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The acts of rubbing other substances into the ball, scratching the surface or picking at the seams constitute illegal ball tampering.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] During normal play, thirteen players and two umpires are on the field.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Two of the players are batters and the rest are all eleven members of the fielding team.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The other nine players in the batting team are off the field in the pavilion.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The image with overlay below shows what is happening when a ball is being bowled and which of the personnel are on or close to the pitch.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In the photo, the two batters (3 and 8, wearing yellow) have taken position at each end of the pitch (6).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Three members of the fielding team (4, 10 and 11, wearing dark blue) are in shot.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] One of the two umpires (1, wearing white hat) is stationed behind the wicket (2) at the bowler's (4) end of the pitch.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The bowler (4) is bowling the ball (5) from their end of the pitch to the batter (8) at the other end who is called the "striker".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The other batter (3) at the bowling end is called the "non-striker".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The wicket-keeper (10), who is a specialist, is positioned behind the striker's wicket (9), and behind them stands one of the fielders in a position called "first slip" (11).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] While the bowler and the first slip are wearing conventional kit only, the two batters and the wicket-keeper are wearing protective gear, including safety helmets, padded gloves and leg guards (pads).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The wicket-keeper is the only fielding player able to wear protective gloves.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] While the umpire (1) in shot stands at the bowler's end of the pitch, their colleague stands in the outfield, usually in or near the fielding position called "square leg", so that they are in line with the popping crease (7) at the striker's end of the pitch.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The bowling crease (not numbered) is the one on which the wicket is located between the return creases (12).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The bowler (4) intends to hit the wicket (9) with the ball (5) or at least prevent the striker (8) from scoring runs.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The striker (8) intends, by using their bat, to defend their wicket and, if possible, hit the ball away from the pitch in order to score runs.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Some players are skilled in both batting and bowling, so are termed all-rounders.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Bowlers are classified according to their style and speed, generally as fast bowlers, seam bowlers or spinners.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Batters are classified according to whether they are right-handed or left-handed, with switch-hitting uncommon and largely utilised as a tactic, where a batter changes stance shortly before the bowler releases the ball.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The Laws state that, throughout an innings, "the ball shall be bowled from each end alternately in overs of 6 balls".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The name "over" came about because the umpire calls "Over!" when six legal balls (deliveries) have been bowled.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] At this point, another bowler is deployed at the other end, and the fielding side changes ends while the batters do not.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] A bowler cannot bowl two successive overs, although a bowler can (and usually does) bowl alternate overs, from the same end, for several overs which are termed a "spell"; if the captain wants a bowler to "change ends", another bowler must temporarily fill in so that the change is not immediate.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The batters do not change ends at the end of the over, and so the one who was non-striker is now the striker and vice versa.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The umpires also change positions so that the one who was at "square leg" now stands behind the wicket at the nonstriker's end and vice versa.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Of the eleven fielders, three are in shot in the image above.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The other eight are elsewhere on the field, their positions determined on a tactical basis by the captain or the bowler.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Fielders often change position between deliveries, again as directed by the captain or bowler.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] If a fielder is injured or becomes ill during a match, a substitute is allowed to field instead of the aforementioned fielder, but the substitute cannot bowl or act as a captain, except in the case of concussion substitutes in international cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The substitute leaves the field when the injured player is fit to return.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The *Laws of Cricket* were updated in 2017 to allow substitutes to act as wicket-keepers.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Batters take turns to bat via a batting order which is decided beforehand by the team captain and presented to the umpires, though the order remains flexible when the captain officially nominates the team.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Substitute batters are generally not allowed, except in the case of concussion substitutes in international cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In order to begin batting the batter first adopts a batting stance.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Standardly, this involves adopting a slight crouch with the feet pointing across the front of the wicket, looking in the direction of the bowler, and holding the bat so it passes over the feet and so its tip can rest on the ground near to the toes of the back foot.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] A skilled batter can use a wide array of "shots" or "strokes" in both defensive and attacking mode.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The idea is to hit the ball to the best effect with the flat surface of the bat's blade.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] If the ball touches the side of the bat, it is called an "edge".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The batter does not have to play a shot and can allow the ball to go through to the wicket-keeper.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Equally, the batter does not have to attempt a run when hitting the ball with their bat.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Batters do not always seek to hit the ball as hard as possible, and a good player can score runs by simply making a deft stroke with a turn of the wrists, or by simply "blocking" the ball but directing it away from fielders so that the player has time to take a run.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] A wide variety of shots are played, the batter's repertoire including strokes named according to the style of swing and the direction aimed: e.g., "cut", "drive", "hook", and "pull".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Each completed run increments the score of both the team and the striker.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The decision to attempt a run is ideally made by the batter who has the better view of the ball's progress, and this is communicated by calling, usually "yes", "no" or "wait".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] More than one run can be scored from a single hit.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Hits worth one to three runs are common, but the size of the field is such that it is usually difficult to run four or more.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] To compensate for this, hits that reach the boundary of the field are automatically awarded four runs if the ball touches the ground *en route* to the boundary or six runs if the ball clears the boundary without touching the ground within the boundary.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In these cases the batters do not need to run.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Hits for five are unusual and generally rely on the help of "overthrows" by a fielder returning the ball.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] If an odd number of runs is scored by the striker, the two batters have changed ends, and the one who was non-striker is now the striker.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Only the striker can score individual runs, but all runs are added to the team's total.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Additional runs can be gained by the batting team as extras (called "sundries" in Australia) due to errors made by the fielding side.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] If the bowler has bowled an illegal delivery (i.e., a no-ball or a wide), the bowler's team incurs an additional penalty because that ball (i.e., delivery) has to be bowled again, and hence the batting side has the opportunity to score more runs from this extra ball.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In addition, the ways in which the batters can be dismissed on an illegal delivery greatly narrow down; in the case of a no-ball, which is the more egregious type of illegal delivery, the only common way in which the batters can be dismissed is by being run out.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] There are nine ways in which a batter can be dismissed: five relatively common and four extremely rare.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] When a batter is dismissed, they are said to have 'lost their wicket', and are barred from batting again in that inning; their team is also said to have 'lost a wicket'.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Once a team has lost 10 wickets, its innings is over.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Most common dismissals involve the wickets, such as when the ball is bowled at the striker's wicket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The Laws state that the fielding team, usually the bowler in practice, must appeal for a dismissal before the umpire can give their decision.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] If the batter is out, the umpire raises a forefinger and says "Out!"; otherwise, the umpire will shake their head and say "Not out".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] There is, effectively, a tenth method of dismissal, retired out (self-dismissal – generally permanent except in cases of injury), which is not an on-field dismissal as such but rather a retrospective one for which no fielder is credited.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Most bowlers are considered specialists in that they are selected for the team because of their skill as a bowler, although some are all-rounders, and even specialist batters bowl occasionally.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] These specialists bowl "spells" that are generally 4 to 8 overs long in order not to physically exhaust the bowler, cause muscle strain and stress the skeleton.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The rules prevent a single bowler from bowling consecutive overs, resulting in at least two bowlers alternating each over.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] If the captain wants a bowler to "change ends", another bowler must temporarily fill in so that the change is not immediate.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The action of bowling the ball is akin to throwing, with the caveat that a bowler's elbow extension is almost entirely restricted, resulting in most bowlers maintaining a straight arm when releasing the ball during their delivery stride.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Additionally, while the bowler is not required to pitch (bounce) the ball, a full toss (non-bouncing) delivery that reaches the striker above waist height is penalised as a no-ball.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] A bowler reaches their delivery stride by means of a "run-up", and an over is deemed to have begun when the bowler starts their run-up for the first delivery of that over, the ball then being "in play".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Fast bowlers, or pacemen, need momentum, taking a lengthy run up, while bowlers with a slow delivery take no more than a couple of steps before bowling.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The fastest bowlers can deliver the ball at a speed of over 145 kilometres per hour (90 mph), and they sometimes rely on sheer speed to try to defeat the batter, who is forced to react very quickly.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Other fast bowlers rely on a mixture of speed and guile by making the ball seam or swing (i.e., curve) in flight.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] This type of delivery can deceive a batter into miscuing their shot, for example, so that the ball just touches the edge of the bat and can then be "caught behind" by the wicket-keeper or a slip fielder.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] At the other end of the bowling scale is the spin bowler, who bowls at a relatively slow pace and relies entirely on guile to deceive the batter.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] A spinner will often "buy their wicket" by "tossing one up" (in a slower, steeper parabolic path) to lure the batter into making a poor shot.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The batter has to be very wary of such deliveries, as the batter is often "flighted" or spun so that the ball will not behave quite as the batter expects it to, and the batter could be "trapped" into getting themself out.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Accidental full toss deliveries can also get wickets, as the failure of the ball to bounce can surprise a batter or induce a poor stroke in an effort to punish the poor delivery with a boundary hit.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In between the pacemen and the spinners are the medium-paced seamers, who rely on persistent accuracy to try to contain the rate of scoring and wear down the batter's concentration.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The captain is often the most experienced player in the team, certainly the most tactically astute, and can possess any of the main skillsets as a batter, a bowler or a wicket-keeper.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Within the Laws, the captain has certain responsibilities in terms of nominating their players to the umpires before the match and ensuring that the captain's players conduct themselves "within the spirit and traditions of the game as well as within the Laws".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The wicket-keeper (sometimes called simply the "keeper") is a specialist fielder subject to various rules within the Laws about their equipment and demeanour.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The wicket-keeper is the only member of the fielding side who can effect a stumping and is the only one permitted to wear gloves and external leg guards.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Depending on their primary skills, the other ten players in the team tend to be classified as specialist batters or specialist bowlers.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Generally, a team will include five or six specialist batters, and four or five specialist bowlers, plus the wicket-keeper.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] There are a number of ways that a cricket match can end and its result be described, depending on whether the team batting first or last wins as well as the format of the game.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] If the team batting last is 'all out' having scored fewer runs than their opponents, they are said to have "lost by *n* runs" (where *n* is the difference between the aggregate number of runs scored by the teams).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] If the team that bats last scores enough runs to win, it is said to have "won by *n* wickets", where *n* is the number of wickets left to fall (batters yet to be dismissed) until the team would have been all out.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In a two-innings-a-side match, one team's combined first and second innings total may be less than the other side's first innings total.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The team with the greater score is then said to have "won by an innings and *n* runs" and does not need to bat again: *n* is the difference between the two teams' aggregate scores.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] If the team batting last is all out and both sides have scored the same number of runs, then the match is a tie; this result is quite rare in matches of two innings a side with only 62 happening in first-class matches from the earliest known instance in 1741 until January 2017.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In the traditional form of the game, if the time allotted for the match expires before either side can win, then the game is declared a draw.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] If the match has only a single innings per side, then usually a maximum number of overs applies to each innings.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Such a match is called a "limited overs" or "one-day" match, and the side scoring more runs wins regardless of the number of wickets lost, so that a draw cannot occur.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In some cases, ties are broken by having each team bat for a one-over innings known as a Super Over; subsequent Super Overs may be played if the first Super Over ends in a tie.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] If this kind of match is temporarily interrupted by bad weather, then a complex mathematical formula, known as the Duckworth–Lewis–Stern (DLS) method after its developers, is often used to recalculate a new target score.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] A one-day match can also be declared a "no-result" if fewer than a previously agreed number of overs have been bowled by either team, in circumstances that make normal resumption of play impossible, for example, wet weather.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In all forms of cricket, the umpires can abandon the match if bad light or rain makes it impossible to continue.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] There have been instances of entire matches, even Test matches scheduled to be played over five days, being lost to bad weather without a ball being bowled, for example, the third Test of the 1970/71 series in Australia.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The innings (ending with 's' in both singular and plural form) is the term used for each phase of play during a match.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Depending on the type of match being played, each team has either one or two innings.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Sometimes all eleven members of the batting side take a turn to bat but, for various reasons, an innings can end before they have all done so.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The innings terminates if the batting team is "all out", a term defined by the Laws: "At the fall of a wicket or the retirement of a batter, further balls remain to be bowled but no further batter is available to come in".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In this situation, one of the batters has not been dismissed and is termed not out; this is because they have no partners left and there must always be two active batters while the innings is in progress.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The game on the field is regulated by the two umpires, one of whom stands behind the wicket at the bowler's end and the other in a position called "square leg", which is about 15–20 m (49–66 ft) away from the batter on strike and in line with the popping crease on which that umpire is taking guard.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The umpires are authorised to interrupt or even abandon a match due to circumstances likely to endanger the players, such as a damp pitch or deterioration of the light.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Off the field in televised matches, there is usually a third umpire who can make decisions on certain incidents with the aid of video evidence.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The third umpire is mandatory under the playing conditions for Test and Limited Overs International matches played between two ICC full member countries.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] These matches also have a match referee whose job is to ensure that play is within the Laws and the spirit of the game.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The match details, including runs and dismissals, are recorded by two official scorers, one representing each team.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The scorers are directed by the hand signals of an umpire (see image, right).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] For example, the umpire raises a forefinger to signal that the batter is out (has been dismissed); the umpire raises both arms above their head if the batter has hit the ball for six runs.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The scorers are required by the Laws to record all runs scored, wickets taken, and overs bowled; in practice, they also note significant amounts of additional data relating to the game.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] A match's statistics are summarised on a scorecard.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Prior to the popularisation of scorecards, most scoring was done by men sitting on vantage points cuttings notches on tally sticks, and runs were originally called notches.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] According to historian Rowland Bowen, the earliest known scorecard templates were introduced in 1776 by T.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Pratt of Sevenoaks and soon came into general use.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] It is believed that scorecards were printed and sold at Lord's for the first time in 1846.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Scores are displayed differently depending on location, although it is standard to show how many wickets have been lost and how many runs a team has made.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Within Australia, the format is Wickets/Runs, while in the rest of the world, the format is Runs/Wickets.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] For example, a score of 125 runs with 4 wickets lost would be displayed as 4/125 or 125/4, respectively.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Besides observing the Laws, cricketers must respect the "Spirit of Cricket", a concept encompassing sportsmanship, fair play and mutual respect.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] This spirit has long been considered an integral part of the sport but is only nebulously defined.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Amidst concern that the spirit was weakening, in 2000, a Preamble was added to the Laws instructing all participants to play within the spirit of the game.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The Preamble is a short statement intended to emphasise the "positive behaviours that make cricket an exciting game that encourages leadership, friendship, and teamwork".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Its second line states that, "the major responsibility for ensuring fair play rests with the captains, but extends to all players, match officials and, especially in junior cricket, teachers, coaches and parents".
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The umpires are the sole judges of fair and unfair play.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] They are required under the Laws to intervene in case of dangerous or unfair play or in cases of unacceptable conduct by a player.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The terse expression of the Spirit of Cricket now avoids trying to enumerate the diverse cultural conventions that exist in the detail of sportsmanship, or its absence.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] Women's cricket was first recorded in Surrey in 1745.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] International development began at the start of the 20th century, and the first Test match was played between Australia and England in December 1934.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The following year, New Zealand joined them, and in 2007 Netherland became the tenth women's Test nation when they made their debut against South Africa.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In 1958, the International Women's Cricket Council was founded (it merged with the ICC in 2005).
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In 1973, the first Cricket World Cup of any kind took place when a Women's World Cup was held in England.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In 2005, the International Women's Cricket Council was merged with the International Cricket Council (ICC) to form one unified body to help manage and develop cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] The ICC Women's Rankings were launched on 1 October 2015 covering all three formats of women's cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p01] In October 2018 following the ICC's decision to award T20 International status to all members, the Women's rankings were split into separate ODI (for Full Members) and T20I lists.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The International Cricket Council (ICC), which has its headquarters in Dubai, is the global governing body of cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] It was founded as the Imperial Cricket Conference in 1909 by representatives from England, Australia and South Africa, renamed the International Cricket Conference in 1965 and took up its current name in 1989.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The ICC in 2017 has 105 member nations, twelve of which hold full membership and can play Test cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The ICC is responsible for the organisation and governance of cricket's major international tournaments, notably the men's and women's versions of the Cricket World Cup.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] It also appoints the umpires and referees that officiate at all sanctioned Test matches, Limited Overs Internationals and Twenty20 Internationals.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Each member nation has a national cricket board which regulates cricket matches played in its country, selects the national squad, and organises home and away tours for the national team.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] In the West Indies, which for cricket purposes is a federation of nations, these matters are addressed by Cricket West Indies.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Cricket is a multifaceted sport with multiple formats that can effectively be divided into first-class cricket, limited overs cricket, and historically, single wicket cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The highest standard is Test cricket (always written with a capital "T") which is in effect the international version of first-class cricket and is restricted to teams representing the twelve countries that are full members of the ICC (see above).
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Although the term "Test match" was not coined until much later, Test cricket is deemed to have begun with two matches between Australia and England in the 1876–77 Australian season; since 1882, most Test series between England and Australia have been played for a trophy known as The Ashes.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The term "first-class", in general usage, is applied to top-level domestic cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Test matches are played over five days and first-class over three to four days; in all of these matches, the teams are allotted two innings each and the draw is a valid result.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Limited overs cricket is always scheduled for completion in a single day, and the teams are allotted one innings each.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] There are two main types: List A which normally allows fifty overs per team; and Twenty20 in which the teams have twenty overs each.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Both of the limited overs forms are played internationally as Limited Overs Internationals (LOI) and Twenty20 Internationals (T20I).
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] List A was introduced in England in the 1963 season as a knockout cup contested by the first-class county clubs.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] In 1969, a national league competition was established.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The concept was gradually introduced to the other leading cricket countries and the first limited overs international was played in 1971.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] In 1975, the first Cricket World Cup took place in England.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Twenty20 is a new variant of limited overs itself with the purpose being to complete the match within about three to four hours, usually in an evening session.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The first Twenty20 World Championship was held in 2007.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] In addition, a few full-member cricket boards have decided to start leagues that are played in the T10 format, in which games are intended to last approximately 90 minutes.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Most recently, in 2021, the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) introduced a new league featuring a hundred-ball tournament, known as The Hundred.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Limited overs matches cannot be drawn, although a tie is possible and an unfinished match is a "no result".
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Single wicket was popular in the 18th and 19th centuries, and its matches were generally considered top-class.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] In this form, although each team may have from one to six players, there is only one batter in at a time, and that batter must face every delivery bowled while their innings lasts.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Single wicket has rarely been played since limited overs cricket began.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Matches tended to have two innings per team like a full first-class one and they could end in a draw.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Cricket is played at both the international and domestic level.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] There is one major international championship per format, and top-level domestic competitions mirror the three main international formats.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] There are now a number of T20 leagues, which have spawned a "T20 freelancer" phenomenon.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Most international matches are played as parts of 'tours', when one nation travels to another for a number of weeks or months, and plays a number of matches of various sorts against the host nation.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Sometimes a perpetual trophy is awarded to the winner of the Test series, the most famous of which is The Ashes.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The ICC also organises competitions that are for several countries at once, including the ICC Men's Cricket World Cup, ICC T20 World Cup and ICC Champions Trophy.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] A league competition for Test matches played as part of normal tours, the ICC World Test Championship, had been proposed several times, and its first instance began in 2019.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] A league competition for ODIs, the ICC Cricket World Cup Super League, began in August 2020 and lasted only for one edition.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The ICC maintains Test rankings, ODI rankings and T20 rankings systems for the countries which play these forms of cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Competitions for member nations of the ICC with Associate status include the ICC Intercontinental Cup, for first-class cricket matches, and the World Cricket League for one-day matches, the final matches of which now also serve as the ICC World Cup Qualifier.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The game's only appearance in an Olympic Games was the 1900 Olympics.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] However, it is scheduled to make a return, with the T20 format of the game, in the 2028 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] First-class cricket in England is played for the most part by the 18 county clubs which contest the County Championship.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The concept of a champion county has existed since the 18th century but the official competition was not established until 1890.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The most successful club has been Yorkshire, who had won 32 official titles (plus one shared) as of 2019.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Australia established its national first-class championship in 1892–93 when the Sheffield Shield was introduced.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] In Australia, the first-class teams represent the various states.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] New South Wales has the highest number of titles.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The world's earliest known cricket match was a village cricket meeting in Kent which has been deduced from a 1640 court case recording a "cricketing" of "the Weald and the Upland" versus "the Chalk Hill" at Chevening "about thirty years since" (i.e., c.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Inter-parish contests became popular in the first half of the 17th century and continued to develop through the 18th with the first local leagues being founded in the second half of the 19th.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] At the grassroots level, local club cricket is essentially an amateur pastime for those involved but still usually involves teams playing in competitions at weekends or in the evening.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Schools cricket, first known in southern England in the 17th century, has a similar scenario and both are widely played in the countries where cricket is popular.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Although there can be variations in game format, compared with professional cricket, the Laws are always observed and club/school matches are therefore formal and competitive events.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The sport has numerous informal variants such as French cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Cricket has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the Commonwealth of Nations and elsewhere.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] It has, for example, influenced the lexicon of these nations, especially the English language, with various phrases such as "that's not cricket" (that's unfair), "had a good innings" (lived a long life), and "sticky wicket".
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] "On a sticky wicket" (*aka* "sticky dog" or "glue pot") is a metaphor used to describe a difficult circumstance.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] It originated as a term for difficult batting conditions in cricket, caused by a damp and soft pitch.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Cricket is the subject of works by noted English poets, including William Blake and Lord Byron.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] *Beyond a Boundary* (1963), written by Trinidadian C.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] James, is often named the best book on any sport ever written.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Francis Bacon, an avid cricket fan, captured a batter in motion.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] In music, many calypsos make reference to the Sport of Cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] See List of calypso songs about cricket.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Cricket has close historical ties with Australian rules football and many players have competed at top levels in both sports.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] In 1858, prominent Australian cricketer Tom Wills called for the formation of a "foot-ball club" with "a code of laws" to keep cricketers fit during the off-season.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The Melbourne Football Club was founded the following year, and Wills and three other members codified the first laws of the game.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] It is typically played on modified cricket fields.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] In England, a number of association football clubs owe their origins to cricketers who sought to play football as a means of keeping fit during the winter months.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Derby County was founded as a branch of the Derbyshire County Cricket Club in 1884; Aston Villa (1874) and Everton (1876) were both founded by members of church cricket teams.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] Sheffield United's Bramall Lane ground was, from 1854, the home of the Sheffield Cricket Club, and then of Yorkshire; it was not used for football until 1862 and was shared by Yorkshire and Sheffield United from 1889 to 1973.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] In the late 19th century, a former cricketer, English-born Henry Chadwick of Brooklyn, New York, was credited with devising the baseball box score (which he adapted from the cricket scorecard) for reporting game events.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The first box score appeared in an 1859 issue of the *Clipper*.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The statistical record is so central to the game's "historical essence" that Chadwick is sometimes referred to as "the Father of Baseball" because he facilitated the popularity of the sport in its early days.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The influence of cricket and other English sports in British India resulted in the local sports becoming standardised by the 1920s.
[src:cricket/cricket-p02] The 21st century success of the Indian Premier League also inspired the growth of other sports leagues in India, with some of the native sports being further modernised, as with the popular Pro Kabaddi League.
